[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Who am I and what is my motivation?  My name is Jonas Hacker, I’m an International Master and chess coach. Working with players of different levels, I’ve seen that you can often achieve very good results with surprising and aggressive openings.  This experience has motivated me to present a complete repertoire after 1.e4 e5 where White leaves the well-known paths early, in no way to hide, but to attack as soon as possible.  What is this course about?  This course is a repertoire for White after the opening moves 1.e4 e5. We start with an Italian set-up, but then leave the main lines on moves four and five. Against the Petrov, Philidor and rare black moves we play direct, often tactical variations with early complications.  Why did I choose this opening?  When working on openings, it often seemed to me that Black is very well prepared in the main lines against the Spanish and Italian. I found it difficult to get an advantage out of the opening, as it is hard to surprise opponents on familiar ground.  While looking for alternatives, I then came across the Romantic Italian - some side variations that are rarely played nowadays. I realized that Black is often taken by surprise and left without preparation.   A closer look at the variations then confirmed that Black often has to play very precisely in order to keep the balance. I therefore consider the Romantic Italian to be an extremely dangerous weapon in practice.  How did I choose my variations?  I have chosen the variations in this course in such a way that the opponents have to make as many difficult decisions as possible as early as possible.  On the one hand, I have chosen many surprises that are often only ranked third or fourth in popularity and in the assessment of modern engines, although they are both interesting and correct. This approach has the advantage that opponents often don't have our ideas on their radar.  Secondly, I have made sure that the black path to equality is as narrow as possible - this means that not all replies equalize, but at best only one.   At the same time, the variations are still solid, so you can play the repertoire even if your opponents are familiar with the opening. The repertoire often works according to the following pattern: Black has to avoid falling for a few direct traps. If they don’t manage to do so, we win immediately - if they do, we start the game in an equal or slightly better position.  I wish you lots of fun and success with my course! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 1A | Elephant Gambit 2...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ In the first chapter we look at all the minor variations, i.e. all the black alternatives to  2...Nc6  ,  2...d6  and  2...Nf6  . Most of them are not good openings. If Black plays such a line, it is usually mainly with the intention of bringing a surprise to the board.  We will try to play simple yet effective ways to gain an advantage against all these surprises. After all, who can and wants to memorize long theoretical variations against rare variations and then rely solely on memory at the board…?!  We won't always maximize our advantage this way, but we will still gain greater advantages than in the 'main variations'. This is, in my opinion, perfectly satisfactory and a very practical approach. }
2... d5
{ The Queen's Pawn Countergambit, sometimes also called the elephant gambit. Not a particularly good choice for Black, but it at least offers some pitfalls and in blitz chess it has found some strong supporters. }
3. exd5 Bd6
{ Black doesn't even think about getting the d5-pawn back. Instead, the plan is to seek counterplay on the kingside and in the centre with ...e5-e4, or the pawn mass e5, f5. White counters best directly in the centre! }
4. d4 e4 5. Ne5
{ Now the knight has a good outpost and Black doesn't have enough compensation }
5... Nf6 6. Bb5+
{ The most direct and easiest way. No answer is satisfactory for Black. } 6...
c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Ba4 Bxe5
{ This looks interesting because it worsens the white king’s position, but Black still has problems. }
9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Ng4 11. Ke1
{ My favourite. With the king on e2 you have to constantly think about ...Ba6+. Black will now have problems developing the queenside because the c6-pawn needs protection. White, on the other hand, still has to solve the problem of how to get the h1-rook into play. It will turn out, however, that Black has more difficulty solving the problems.  Let's see a possible continuation:  11...Nxe5  12.Bf4  Ng6  13.Be3  f5  14.Nc3  Be6  15.Rd1  − White is faster and already threatens Rd6.  15...Kf7  16.Ne2  − controls the square  f4  and makes sure that f2-f3 cannot be followed by ...f5-f4 and ...e4-e3.  16...Rc8  17.Nd4  Ne7  18.f3  . White opens the position. This not only helps the bishops, but also makes it easy to bring the rook from h1 into play. For example with Kf2 and Re1, or directly via f1 if the f-file opens up. }
