1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ In the first chapter we look at all the minor variations, i.e. all the black alternatives to  2...Nc6  ,  2...d6  and  2...Nf6  . Most of them are not good openings. If Black plays such a line, it is usually mainly with the intention of bringing a surprise to the board.  We will try to play simple yet effective ways to gain an advantage against all these surprises. After all, who can and wants to memorize long theoretical variations against rare variations and then rely solely on memory at the board…?!  We won't always maximize our advantage this way, but we will still gain greater advantages than in the 'main variations'. This is, in my opinion, perfectly satisfactory and a very practical approach. }
2... f6
{ A dubious move. Black moves the f-pawn, weakens the king and takes away the f6-square from the knight. Apart from the general disadvantages, White can refute the variation immediately. }
3. Nxe5 fxe5 { This allows White to attack strongly or win material. } 4. Qh5+
Ke7 5. Qxe5+ Kf7 6. Bc4+ d5
{ Black opens the diagonal for the c8-bishop and thus controls the important f5-square. Nevertheless, White is already winning. Three central pawns for the sacrificed piece and the weak black king are too much. }
7. Bxd5+ Kg6 8. h4
{ The attack continues and White has several continuations to choose from. Note that now  8...h6  can be answered with  9.Bxb7  . The bishop is taboo because of  9...Bxb7  10.Qf5#  . }
