[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov. It is considered one of the most solid openings for Black, but requires accuracy. Another disadvantage for Black is that White can keep the game relatively symmetrical if they wish in order to minimise Black's chances of winning.   Nevertheless, we will try to find interesting and not necessarily symmetrical ways to make life difficult for Black. We also try to keep the variations simple, as the Petroff is much less common than the Italian. }
3. Nxe5
{ The main line. Alternatively, moves such as  3.Nc3  , with a transition to the Four Knights Game, or the forcing  3.d4  are also possible. }
3... Nc6
{ The Stafford Gambit. Not good, but tricky and quite popular in online chess. }
4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ This is the usual move. Black quickly opens all lines and diagonals for the pieces.   Why is Black's game still doomed to failure? White has no weaknesses and also has two centre pawns, the d-pawn and the e-pawn. These can - if used correctly - block the black piece play. }
5. d3 { White stabilises the position. } 5... Bc5
{ Now ...Ng4 is a threat, but White can easily parry it. } 6. Be2 Ng4
{ This is premature. Black will soon win back the sacrificed piece, but White can exchange pieces and fend off all direct threats. }
7. Bxg4 Qh4 8. Qf3 Bxg4 9. Qg3
{ White consolidates here as well. Black has to avoid exchanging queens, but this gives White the time needed to continue the development. }
