1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov. It is considered one of the most solid openings for Black, but requires accuracy. Another disadvantage for Black is that White can keep the game relatively symmetrical if they wish in order to minimise Black's chances of winning.   Nevertheless, we will try to find interesting and not necessarily symmetrical ways to make life difficult for Black. We also try to keep the variations simple, as the Petroff is much less common than the Italian. }
3. Nxe5
{ The main line. Alternatively, moves such as  3.Nc3  , with a transition to the Four Knights Game, or the forcing  3.d4  are also possible. }
3... Nxe4 { This is not advisable for Black, but not immediately lost either. }
4. Qe2
{ White exploits the opposition on the e-file by being a bit faster creating the first threats. Black must sacrifice a piece immediately, otherwise White wins the queen and the game. }
4... Qe7 5. Qxe4
{ White collects the material, but is prepared to give some of it back later under good conditions. }
5... d6
{ Black immediately uses the pin on the e-file to win back the piece. In doing so, Black also clears the way for further pieces, here the bishop on c8.   5...Nc6?  6.d4  d6  is a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppppqppp/8/4N3/4Q3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  6.d4  Nc6  . }
6. d4 { This strengthens the centre and prepares the development } 6... dxe5 7.
dxe5 Nc6 8. Nc3
{ The exclamation mark is not only for the strength of the move, but also for its simplicity. White gives up the pawn and relies on activity. }
8... Qxe5 9. Qxe5+ Nxe5 10. Bf4
{ The bishop attacks the unprotected knight. It must be protected and cannot move itself, as the c7-pawn would drop. }
10... Bd6 11. Bg3 a6 12. Ne4
{ This is similar to the variation with 11...Bd7: Black gets a weak pawn on d6. }
