[Black "QS | 4A | Petrov Main 6...Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov. It is considered one of the most solid openings for Black, but requires accuracy. Another disadvantage for Black is that White can keep the game relatively symmetrical if they wish in order to minimise Black's chances of winning.   Nevertheless, we will try to find interesting and not necessarily symmetrical ways to make life difficult for Black. We also try to keep the variations simple, as the Petroff is much less common than the Italian. }
3. Nxe5
{ The main line. Alternatively, moves such as  3.Nc3  , with a transition to the Four Knights Game, or the forcing  3.d4  are also possible. }
3... d6
{ The normal move. Black first drives back the white knight and then wins back the pawn on e4. }
4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5
{ This is by far the most popular move. Black secures the knight and gains space in the center.  Other moves such as  5...Be7  or  5...Nf6  have no individual significance because Black will have to play ...d6-d5 sooner or later anyway. These moves are considered under the sequence  5...d5  6.Bd3  Be7  and  6...Nf6  respectively. }
6. Bd3
{ White develops the bishop to the most active square d3. In many Petroff games this is the best place for the bishop, as from here it takes part in the later fight for the e4-outpost. At this point Black has a number of possible setups and plans at their disposal. }
6... Bd6
{ The most active way to develop the bishop. From here the bishop looks towards the white kingside and has its eye on the square e5. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Re1
{ This is the position we were aiming for. But why exactly do I think it is a good practical solution? What are the advantages?   ➤ White has more space, which is particularly evident in the pawn pair c4 and c6. We exert pressure on d5 and will decide if and when to capture. We can also consider c4-c5 under good circumstances.   ➤ White threatens, Black reacts. White is always half a move ahead, so it's no surprise that White's threats come earlier. Black has to make many decisions.   Moving away from the general advantages, let's briefly look at the most typical white plans in the given position:   ➤ Challenge the e4 outpost.   ➤ Attack the weaknesses b7 and d5. This is usually done with Qb3 - a move that should be considered especially if Black has moved the c8-bishop and left b7 unprotected.   ➤ Transformation of the central structure: We are usually happy after Nc3, ...Nxc3, bxc3 because we get a more stable centre due to the extra pawn on the c-file. The doubled pawn is also never permanent due to the tension and the possible c4xd5 capture - therefore it cannot be counted as a weakness. This operation also opens up the b-file, which will be useful for the white rook. }
9... Re8 10. Qb3
{ A typical move. White increases the pressure on d5 and also keeps an eye on the b7-pawn, which makes Black's development more difficult. }
10... b6 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Bg5
{ A strong piece sacrifice never seen before in tournament practice. White connects the rooks and gains a decisive initiative, because the entire black queenside is undeveloped. }
12... f6 13. bxc3 fxg5 14. Rxe8+
{ Exchanging the rook is essential for the attack: the black back rank becomes more vulnerable. }
14... Qxe8 15. Re1 Qd8 16. cxd5
{ Now  16...cxd5  cannot follow, because the rook on a8 would hang after  17.Qxd5+  . }
16... c5
{ This is the more tenacious attempt. Black keeps the diagonal a2-g8 closed and tries to slow down the white attack. }
17. dxc5 bxc5
{ The bishop must stay on d6 to prevent d5-d6+ with activation of the white queen. }
18. Nxg5 { Now  18...Qxg5  would be followed by  19.Re8  --  and  20.Rxc8  . }
18... g6 19. Qa4
{ White activates the strongest piece, Re8+, Qc6, and also Qh4 are among the threats. }
19... Bd7 20. Qh4 { White wins by the strong attack. } *

