1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov. It is considered one of the most solid openings for Black, but requires accuracy. Another disadvantage for Black is that White can keep the game relatively symmetrical if they wish in order to minimise Black's chances of winning.   Nevertheless, we will try to find interesting and not necessarily symmetrical ways to make life difficult for Black. We also try to keep the variations simple, as the Petroff is much less common than the Italian. }
3. Nxe5
{ The main line. Alternatively, moves such as  3.Nc3  , with a transition to the Four Knights Game, or the forcing  3.d4  are also possible. }
3... d6
{ The normal move. Black first drives back the white knight and then wins back the pawn on e4. }
4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5
{ This is by far the most popular move. Black secures the knight and gains space in the center.  Other moves such as  5...Be7  or  5...Nf6  have no individual significance because Black will have to play ...d6-d5 sooner or later anyway. These moves are considered under the sequence  5...d5  6.Bd3  Be7  and  6...Nf6  respectively. }
6. Bd3
{ White develops the bishop to the most active square d3. In many Petroff games this is the best place for the bishop, as from here it takes part in the later fight for the e4-outpost. At this point Black has a number of possible setups and plans at their disposal. }
6... Bd6
{ The most active way to develop the bishop. From here the bishop looks towards the white kingside and has its eye on the square e5. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Re1
{ This is the position we were aiming for. But why exactly do I think it is a good practical solution? What are the advantages?   ➤ White has more space, which is particularly evident in the pawn pair c4 and c6. We exert pressure on d5 and will decide if and when to capture. We can also consider c4-c5 under good circumstances.   ➤ White threatens, Black reacts. White is always half a move ahead, so it's no surprise that White's threats come earlier. Black has to make many decisions.   Moving away from the general advantages, let's briefly look at the most typical white plans in the given position:   ➤ Challenge the e4 outpost.   ➤ Attack the weaknesses b7 and d5. This is usually done with Qb3 - a move that should be considered especially if Black has moved the c8-bishop and left b7 unprotected.   ➤ Transformation of the central structure: We are usually happy after Nc3, ...Nxc3, bxc3 because we get a more stable centre due to the extra pawn on the c-file. The doubled pawn is also never permanent due to the tension and the possible c4xd5 capture - therefore it cannot be counted as a weakness. This operation also opens up the b-file, which will be useful for the white rook. }
9... Bf5 10. Qb3 Qd7
{ Black covers b7 without making any further concessions. In addition, the queen remains on the d-file, so White can't win a pawn on d5 at the moment. }
11. c5 Bc7 12. Nbd2 Re8 13. Nh4 Be6
{ Black defends e4 with a counter-threat.  14.Nxe4  is now followed by  14...dxe4  with a discovery on the white queen. }
14. Qc2 Na6 15. a3
{ White prevents ...Nb4 and threatens to capture on e4. Black must act precisely now. }
15... Bg4
{ This is the best move, but it has never been played outside the top level. Why does Black position the bishop so that White could fork it, while the bishop itself doesn't even attack anything?!  Let's look at this step by step: The fork  16.f3  is countered with the tactical  16...Bd8  and the white knight on the rim also has problems.  In addition, the bishop clears the e-file and prepares counterplay there, so White cannot improve on the queenside without worrying. After  16.b4  , for example,  16...Ng5  would follow, fighting for the e-file. }
16. Nxe4
{ I recommend accepting the challenge.  16.f3?  Bd8!  . Black has to rely on tactical resources here, but it's just enough. }
16... dxe4 17. Rxe4 Rxe4 18. Bxe4 Qxd4
{ Black has won back the pawn first, but must have correctly assessed all the complications in advance, such as Bxh7+ or Be3 and only then Bxh7+. Meanwhile, White still has all the options. }
19. Be3 Qf6
{ The best square for the queen, also because it covers g6 from there. This becomes important as Black wants to pin the bishop after  20.Bxh7+  Kh8  21.g3  g6  . }
20. Nf3
{ This is clearly the more solid choice and has been seen in two grandmaster games so far.   20.Bxh7+!?  can also be explored, but in my opinion it carries more risks for both sides. }
20... Bxf3 21. Bxf3
{ The position is balanced, but White can hope to outplay their opponent in the middlegame/endgame with the two bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 5A | Philidor with 3...Nd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 Nd7
{ Black tries to get into normal closed, i.e. without ...exd4, Philidor positions, but with this move order, they will not succeed. }
4. Bc4
{ This is more accurate than 4.Nc3. Black must now be very careful, because threats like Ng5 or dxe5 and Qd5 are already in the air. The point f7 is, as so often, our target and very vulnerable. }
4... c6
{ The only move that maintains the tension and at the same time does not allow White to use any tactics. }
5. O-O Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Ng5
{ Here a strategic goal is realised with tactical means: White temporarily sacrifices the knight in order to then win the bishop pair. }
7... Bxg5 8. Qh5
{ The point. Mate is threatened and the g5-bishop is attacked. Black can avoid mate, but the bishop is lost. In the resulting endgame White is clearly better. }
8... Qe7 9. Qxg5 Qxg5 10. Bxg5
{ White has a very strong bishop which will work from e3 on both wings. In addition, White can win space on the queenside with a2-a4-a5 or try to be the first to become active on the d-file. }
*

