[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 Nd7
{ Black tries to get into normal closed, i.e. without ...exd4, Philidor positions, but with this move order, they will not succeed. }
4. Bc4
{ This is more accurate than 4.Nc3. Black must now be very careful, because threats like Ng5 or dxe5 and Qd5 are already in the air. The point f7 is, as so often, our target and very vulnerable. }
4... h6 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Bxf7+
{ A somewhat surprising move, Black is already lost } 6... Kxf7 7. Nxe5+
{ The knight cannot be captured, otherwise the black queen will be lost. White already has two pawns for the sacrificed piece and the attack against the exposed king is just beginning. }
7... Kf6 { After  7...Nxe5??  8.Qxd8+-  White is winning the queen. } 8. Nc3
Kxe5 { Brave, but not good. The king gets caught in a strong attack. } 9. Qd5+
Kf6 10. Qf5+ Ke7 11. Nd5+ Kd6 { 11...Ke8??  12.Qg6#  mate. } 12. Bf4+
{ We stop here, White is winning - the black king is too open. White mates or wins material. }
