[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 5E | Philidor with 3...exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 exd4 { 3...Nc6  4.Bc4  transposes to chapter 6, see here. } 4. Nxd4 Nf6
5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bf4
{ White has a lot of alternatives at this point like Be2, Bc4, Be3 and then the choice to castle short or long.   I recommend an active and sharp setup with Qd2 and a quick O-O-O. This set-up is very universal, rarer than other set-ups, dangerous for Black and easy to remember. In the middlegame with unequal castling we often aim for a pawn storm with h4-h5 and f2-f3, g2-g4 }
6... O-O
{ Black can also start with  6...c6  ,  6...c5  ,  6...Nc6  . But since ...O-O is unavoidable, we will only consider this sequence. }
7. Qd2
{ Here we will study Black's most common and typical plans:  ➤  7...Nc6  with normal central piece play.   ➤  7...d5  , a direct attempt to break free.   ➤  7...c6  , a flexible waiting move preparing ...d6-d5.   ➤  7...a6  with the idea of getting activity on the wing with ...b7-b5. }
7... d5 8. Ndb5
{ A typical counter-attack against premature ...d6-d5 ideas. White sets their sights on the weak point c7. }
8... Bb4
{ 8...Na6?  loses the d5-pawn:  9.exd5+-  with an extra pawn and a clear advantage. }
9. O-O-O
{ 9.Nxc7?  is not good here. Black gets more than enough counterplay after  9...d4!  10.O-O-O  Nc6  11.Nxa8  Qa5  with an unclear position. }
9... c6 10. Nc7 Nxe4 11. Qd4
{ The best square for the queen, the b4-bishop is threatened and the next moves are quite forced. }
11... Bc5 12. Qxe4
{ A temporary queen sacrifice. White gets the black queen back immediately. }
12... Qxc7
{ 12...dxe4??  13.Rxd8  loses a lot of material, because the a8-rook will also fall. }
13. Bxc7 dxe4 14. Nxe4
{ With material balance and great initiative for White. } *

