1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 exd4 { 3...Nc6  4.Bc4  transposes to chapter 6, see here. } 4. Nxd4 Nf6
5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bf4
{ White has a lot of alternatives at this point like Be2, Bc4, Be3 and then the choice to castle short or long.   I recommend an active and sharp setup with Qd2 and a quick O-O-O. This set-up is very universal, rarer than other set-ups, dangerous for Black and easy to remember. In the middlegame with unequal castling we often aim for a pawn storm with h4-h5 and f2-f3, g2-g4 }
6... O-O
{ Black can also start with  6...c6  ,  6...c5  ,  6...Nc6  . But since ...O-O is unavoidable, we will only consider this sequence. }
7. Qd2
{ Here we will study Black's most common and typical plans:  ➤  7...Nc6  with normal central piece play.   ➤  7...d5  , a direct attempt to break free.   ➤  7...c6  , a flexible waiting move preparing ...d6-d5.   ➤  7...a6  with the idea of getting activity on the wing with ...b7-b5. }
7... Nc6 8. O-O-O Nxd4 { 8...Bd7  9.f3  is similar to the mainline. } 9. Qxd4
Be6 10. f3 { We look at a few attempts by Black to become active. } 10... Nd7
11. h4 Bxh4
{ We are not afraid of losing a pawn, as the half-open h-file would only accelerate our attack. }
12. Qd2 Bf6 13. g4 { With excellent play on the h-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 6B | Italian with 3...h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 h6
{ The idea of this move is to play ... Nf6 without having to fear Ng5. Nevertheless, 3...h6 is a bad move because Black loses too much time.   Our antidote to such slow moves is always the same: open the position. In an open position a development advantage will always be more noticeable than in a closed one.   In a closed position there is no direct confrontation and the extra piece does not come into its own. If the position is open, it usually becomes concrete and threats arise. One or two additionally developed pieces can make the difference. }
4. d4
{ The center opens and White threatens dxe5. In contrast to moves like  4.O-O  or  4.Nc3  , Black's room for error is much smaller and another bad move can cost them the game. }
4... d6 { Too slow, White is already winning a pawn. } 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+
{ Now every recapture leads to the loss of a pawn. } 6... Nxd8
{ After  6...Kxd8  7.Bxf7  White also is a healthy pawn up. } 7. Nxe5
{ White has a healthy extra pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 7 | Italian with 4...Nxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Nxd4
{ A rare but good move. In my opinion, it is rarely seen in practice for two reasons:  1@@EndBracket@@ Black must react to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  with  3...exd4  . Our move order is rarer and it's not worth it for Black studying another reply.  2@@EndBracket@@ After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/8/2b1p3/2BnP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxe5  , Black has to play  5...Qe7  and allow themselves to be captured on f7, then play further accurate moves, which many players find impractical in a minor variation. }
5. Nxe5
{ This is my recommendation and true to our approach of playing aggressive variations.   Black has only one good reply and only found it in about 25% of the games played. On all other replies, White gets a big or decisive advantage. Compared to the Blackburne Gambit @@StartBracket@@after 4.d4 Black no longer has the option of playing ...Qg5.@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Qf6
{ A tempting counter-attack: Black threatens the knight and aims with the queen towards f2. }
6. Bxf7+
{ First we destroy the black king’s position and collect a pawn.   6.Nd3  was played in the game Nakamura, H - Sevian, S, 2015 and here, too, White was clearly better. }
6... Kf8 7. Nd3
{ A key motive in this variation. White saves the knight and attacks the bishop on c5, which is unprotected because the black queen is on f6 instead of e7 - a small difference with a big effect.   If Black saves the bishop, White can also save the bishop. If Black takes on f7, White also captures on c5. In addition, the knight covers f2, so we don't have to fear any discovered attacks of the knight from d4. }
7... d6 8. Bh5 Qh4 9. Nxc5 dxc5 10. Bf3
{ White is winning, Black is a pawn down and the king is in a bad position. White can challenge the knight on d4 with Be3 or ...c2-c3. }
*

