{ This is my recommendation and true to our approach of playing aggressive variations.   Black has only one good reply and only found it in about 25% of the games played. On all other replies, White gets a big or decisive advantage. Compared to the Blackburne Gambit @@StartBracket@@after 4.d4 Black no longer has the option of playing ...Qg5.@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Qe7 6. Bxf7+ Kd8 7. Nd3
{ The black queen cannot take on f7, otherwise the c5-bishop would also be lost. }
7... Qxe4+
{ 7...Qxf7??  leaves Black a pawn down and with an insecure king.  8.Nxc5  Qc4  , a tempting attempt to win material, but White can solve the problems tactically and is still winning.  9.Nc3!  Qxc5  10.Be3!  . The point. We win back the piece and Black has massive problems with development and king safety. }
8. Kf1 b6 9. Nc3 Qf5 10. Bd5 c6 11. Be4 Qe6 12. Nxc5 bxc5 13. Bd3
{ White has the bishop pair and is clearly better. } *

