1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Bxd4
{ In the main chapter on this variation we'll take a closer look at the move 4...Bxd4. It is the second most popular move and a good answer. }
5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Be3
{ A relatively unexplored idea. White confronts Black with a difficult question: should you try to keep the extra pawn or should you try to finish the development quickly instead?   6.O-O  is the 'normal' way for White. White goes for quick development and tries to open the position with f2-f4, f4xe5 and Bg5.  6...Nf6  7.f4  d6  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.Bg5  . However, this approach has already been tried in more than 1000 games and, in my opinion, can neither surprise Black nor pose any serious problems. }
6... Nc6
{ The most popular reply. Black secures the knight and extra pawn.  However, White has two active bishops and can now target the weak points f7 or g7 with the queen. Both moves,  7.Qh5  and  7.Qg4  allow Black to equalise, but there are some difficulties to overcome on the way. }
7. Qg4 Kf8
{ This is already a major concession. Black loses the castling right forever, which already gives us sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
8. Qe2 { ...d7-d5 was threatened with a piece win. } 8... Nf6 9. Nc3 d6 10. O-O
{ We play simple development moves, while Black already has to solve concrete problems: How to untangle on the kingside?   10.O-O-O  is another equivalent option that can be explored further. }
10... Be6 { A natural try, Black neutralises the strong c4-bishop. } 11. Bxe6
fxe6 12. f4
{ White should always fight for the initiative and create threats as long as Black is uncoordinated. }
12... exf4 13. Bxf4
{ The position remains dangerous for Black along the f-file } 13... h6
{ Black prevents Bg5, but not... } 14. e5 dxe5 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. Qxe5
{ White has successfully opened the position and is ready to bring in more forces with Rad1, Ne4 or Rae1. }
16... Qd6 { Black cannot relieve themselves by exchanging queens. } 17. Rxf6+
gxf6 18. Qxf6+ Kg8 19. Qg6+ Kf8 20. Rf1+ Ke7 21. Qg7+
{ White wins at least both rooks. } *

