{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Bxd4
{ In the main chapter on this variation we'll take a closer look at the move 4...Bxd4. It is the second most popular move and a good answer. }
5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Be3
{ A relatively unexplored idea. White confronts Black with a difficult question: should you try to keep the extra pawn or should you try to finish the development quickly instead?   6.O-O  is the 'normal' way for White. White goes for quick development and tries to open the position with f2-f4, f4xe5 and Bg5.  6...Nf6  7.f4  d6  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.Bg5  . However, this approach has already been tried in more than 1000 games and, in my opinion, can neither surprise Black nor pose any serious problems. }
6... Nc6
{ The most popular reply. Black secures the knight and extra pawn.  However, White has two active bishops and can now target the weak points f7 or g7 with the queen. Both moves,  7.Qh5  and  7.Qg4  allow Black to equalise, but there are some difficulties to overcome on the way. }
7. Qg4 Qf6
{ This has been played almost exclusively so far. Black protects g7 without irreversibly weakening the structure with ...g7-g6 and sets up the threat ...d7-d5 winning a piece. }
8. Nc3
{ Provocative, but strong! What do you think White has planned after the discovered attack with  8...d5 ? }
8... d5
{ This is a tempting move and has been played in the majority of games. However, White has a strong silent reply which Black can easily overlook. }
9. Qg3 dxc4
{ Now there was no way back, otherwise Black simply loses the pawn on d5, while White keeps the development advantage on top. }
10. Nd5 Qg6
{ Black must keep the g7-pawn defended, otherwise a whole rook will be lost after Qxg7. Giving up the a8-rook is the better attempt to hold the position. Then at least Black has the hope of trapping the white knight in the corner. }
11. Nxc7+ Kd8 12. Nxa8
{ The position is already won for White here, but it's worth taking a closer look at a few more tactical ideas. Black has several ideas to trap the knight, but none of them work. }
12... Qxg3
{ The best attempt for Black is to exchange queens. Otherwise, the white queen often becomes active and the black king comes under attack. }
13. O-O-O+
{ It is important to give the check before Black has cleared the c8-square for the king.   13.hxg3?!  Be6  14.O-O-O+ ?  Kc8!  would be anything but clear. }
13... Bd7 14. fxg3
{ An important nuance: the rook can now quickly enter the game via the f-file. This opens up too many fronts and it becomes impossible for Black to trap the knight in the corner.   14.hxg3  Nf6  is also better for White but less convincing. }
14... Nf6
{ The primary difficulty in picking up the knight with ...Kc8-b8 is the unprotected bishop on d7. This is shown, for example, by the variation  14...Kc8  15.Bxa7  Nxa7  and  16.Nb6  with a double attack and material gain for White.  It is therefore first necessary to cover the bishop on d7 with the help of 14...Nf6 in order to be able to continue with ...Kc8.  In the case of fxg3, however, this doesn't work because the white rook will soon eliminate the knight on f6. }
15. Rhf1
{ This is our key move. Black can't parry the threatened exchange sacrifice. }
15... Kc8 16. Bxa7 Nxa7 17. Rxf6 { Now the d7-bishop is only protected once. }
17... gxf6 18. Nb6+
{ White wins, we have an extra pawn and Black has further weaknesses on c4 and f6. }
