[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 10 | Italian with 4...exd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... exd4 5. Ng5
{ A rare and very forcing move that immediately confronts Black with the weakness of the f7-pawn. We should memorise 2 basic rules.  ➤ Our plan is to capture on f7 in any case, even if Black protects with  5...Ne5  or  5...Nh6  . This always works because after  6.Nxf7  Nxf7  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  we win back the bishop on c5 with 8  .Qh5+  .  ➤ On ...Bb4+ @@StartBracket@@to remove the bishop from c5 so that Qh5+ won't be a double attack@@EndBracket@@ we always reply c2-c3 with a counterattack on the bishop. }
5... Nh6
{ This is the only good reply. Black places the knight on the edge, but brings a new piece into play and prepares castling. Since Black would have no problems after castling, we capture immediately despite the protection. }
6. Nxf7
{ I recommend taking with the knight first, even if it makes no difference in the majority of cases and only leads to a transposition. Nevertheless, in my opinion 6. Nxf7 is more accurate, because here Black has fewer options, namely only ...Nxf7 and ...Bb4+.  In the case of  6.Bxf7+  Nxf7  7.Nxf7  Black would have a greater choice, but we don't want to allow that. In addition to  7...Kxf7  and  7...Bb4  , Black could also try  7...Qh4  or  7...Qe7  . We avoid this with our move order. }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+
{ Now comes the second capture with check and Black has practically no choice. }
7... Kxf7 8. Qh5+ Kf8 9. Qxc5+ d6 10. Qb5 a6 11. Qe2
{ Black must go their own way and has problems to solve. The king is in a strange position and the rook is in the corner. Even if a clever regrouping succeeds, White always has the safer king and more pawns on the kingside, which can be set in motion at the right moment.   In addition, c2-c3 can also be played with rapid development of the b1-knight, or an attempt to win the d4-pawn is also possible. Let's take a look at some of Black's attempts }
11... h6 12. c3
{ A typical motive. Let's take a look at it. Why do we exchange the black doubled pawn?   First, even if d4 is a doubled pawn, it's not that weak, the knight of c6 covers and also ...Qf6 can strengthen it. Moreover, it restricts our natural development with Nc3.   What do we achieve with c3?   We quickly develop our knight to c3 and have opened up the position. Later we can often use the c-file to build up pressure against c7.   If Black doesn't capture on c3, we capture ourselves. ...Nxd4 then comes with tempo, but the knight won't stay long. If Black covers it with ...c5 we always have Be3 and Black is left with many weaknesses. }
12... Kg8 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Qd3 Nc6 15. O-O Kh7 16. Nc3
{ Since we can often achieve such structures, let's take a closer look and try to understand why White has a big advantage here.   Our advantage no longer lies in the development advantage, Black could play ...Rf8 and ...Kg8 to complete the artificial castling.   Instead, our advantage lies in the pawn structure. White has two pawns more on the kingside, while Black has the majority on the queenside. But why exactly are our extra pawns stronger?   ➤ Mobility: It's quite easy to play f2-f4 @@StartBracket@@and perhaps f4-f5-f6@@EndBracket@@ with great control over the centre than ... c7-c5 or ... d6-d5.   ➤ King security: In a middlegame it is often advantageous to have more pawns on the kingside. This often allows the simple plan of exchanging pawns, after which the opponent's king has less pawn protection than yours.   ➤ Stability: It is also possible to play f2-f3 first, bring up pieces and then attack. the construct with pawns on f3 and e4 is extremely stable, as the pawn chain is not weak on the half-open lines e and f. The situation is different for Black: On the half-open c-file, the c7-pawn is potentially weak and needs the sc6-pawn as a shield. If the c-pawn were to move, the d-pawn will become weak on the half-open d-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 10 | Italian with 4...exd4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... exd4 5. Ng5
{ A rare and very forcing move that immediately confronts Black with the weakness of the f7-pawn. We should memorise 2 basic rules.  ➤ Our plan is to capture on f7 in any case, even if Black protects with  5...Ne5  or  5...Nh6  . This always works because after  6.Nxf7  Nxf7  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  we win back the bishop on c5 with 8  .Qh5+  .  ➤ On ...Bb4+ @@StartBracket@@to remove the bishop from c5 so that Qh5+ won't be a double attack@@EndBracket@@ we always reply c2-c3 with a counterattack on the bishop. }
5... Nh6
{ This is the only good reply. Black places the knight on the edge, but brings a new piece into play and prepares castling. Since Black would have no problems after castling, we capture immediately despite the protection. }
6. Nxf7
{ I recommend taking with the knight first, even if it makes no difference in the majority of cases and only leads to a transposition. Nevertheless, in my opinion 6. Nxf7 is more accurate, because here Black has fewer options, namely only ...Nxf7 and ...Bb4+.  In the case of  6.Bxf7+  Nxf7  7.Nxf7  Black would have a greater choice, but we don't want to allow that. In addition to  7...Kxf7  and  7...Bb4  , Black could also try  7...Qh4  or  7...Qe7  . We avoid this with our move order. }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+
{ Now comes the second capture with check and Black has practically no choice. }
7... Kxf7 8. Qh5+ g6
{ This is the best reply. Black must rely on dynamics and quickly look for counterplay. The weakening of the black squares f6, g7, h6 is accepted. }
9. Qxc5
{ 9.Qd5+?!  would only help the black king to leave the centre faster. } 9...
Qe7 10. Qxe7+ Nxe7 11. c3 dxc3 12. Nxc3
{ White is always better in such endgames. The asymmetrical distribution of the pawns is the decisive reason for this.   While the c7-pawn tends to be weak - or in the case of ... c7-c6 the d6-pawn - the white chain in the centre with f3-e4 can never be attacked. Consequently, Black has no clear plan while White can gradually increase the pressure against c7.   Another plan can be to create play on the h-file with h2-h4-h5. }
*

