[Black "QS | 11B | Two Knights with 4...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Nf6 4. Ng5 d5
{ The main and only good reply. Black must interrupt the diagonal of the white bishop to fend off the attack against f7. }
5. exd5 Nxd5
{ A clear mistake, White has two good continuations,  6.Nxf7  and  6.d4  .  I recommend  6.d4  here, we don't necessarily have to sacrifice a piece, but open up the position first in order to maximise our activity. }
6. d4 exd4 7. O-O Be6 8. Re1 Qd7 9. Nxf7
{ A powerful blow, although f7 seemed well covered. In any case, White wins the piece back with interest and the black king is stranded in the centre. }
9... Kxf7
{ 9...Qxf7  10.Bxd5  , Black cannot recapture because of the pin on the e-file. }
10. Qf3+
{ An important check, White brings the queen into play and attacks the d5-square once more. }
10... Kg8 11. Rxe6
{ White exploits the constricted position of the black king on g8. } 11... Qxe6
12. Qxd5 { And mate is coming soon. } *

