[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Nf6 4. Ng5 d5
{ The main and only good reply. Black must interrupt the diagonal of the white bishop to fend off the attack against f7. }
5. exd5 Na5
{ The main variation. Here we will surprise Black with a rare move, which is ten times rarer than the 'normal' 6.Bb5+, but still contains a few challenging ideas. }
6. d3
{ White wants to stay on c4 with the bishop. If Black captures on c4, the pawn on d5 is protected by a pawn and Black cannot get the pawn back.   If Black does not capture on c4, the knight a5 can sometimes remain offside. Of course, Black has ways to equalise the position, but accuracy is required and the surprise effect plays into White's hands. }
6... h6
{ Black is best off questioning the knight immediately to gain the initiative. At the moment the knight can't go to e4 because after  7.Ne4  Nxe4  8.dxe4  Nxc4  Black would win a piece. }
7. Nf3 e4
{ It is imperative that Black continues to play with the initiative, otherwise White will end up with an extra pawn. }
8. Nd4 { A sideline inside the sideline. More common is  8.Qe2  . } 8... Bc5 9.
c3
{ 9.Nb3  allows a typical idea of Black's that you should have seen once and should not allow:  9...Bg4  10.Qd2  Nxc4  11.dxc4  e3  12.fxe3  Ne4  . This is followed by ...Qh4+ and Black wins. }
9... O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. Bb5 Re7 12. dxe4
{ This is now possible because the bishop on c4 is no longer hanging. White temporarily has two extra pawns. Black simply gets the first one back, but not the second - White is better }
