[White "1) Rare 2nd Moves after 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3"]
[Black "1A | Elephant Gambit 2...d5 | 3...Bd6 / 6...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Queen's Pawn Countergambit, sometimes called the elephant gambit. Also not a particularly good choice for Black, but still with some pitfalls. At least in blitz chess it has found some strong supporters. }
3. exd5 Bd6
{ Black doesn't even think about getting the d5-pawn back. Instead, the plan is to seek counterplay with ...e5-e4, or the pawn mass e5 and f5 on the kingside and in the center.   White counters best directly in the center! }
4. d4 e4 5. Ne5
{ Now the knight has a good outpost and Black doesn't have enough compensation }
5... Nf6 6. Bb5+
{ The most direct and easiest way. No answer is satisfactory for Black. } 6...
Nbd7 7. Bg5 O-O 8. Bxd7 Bxd7 9. Nxd7
{ 9.c4  is probably the best move, but Black has certain ideas to destabilize the e5-knight and White has to go through more complications.  Instead, I recommend the simplifying  9.Nxd7  , which weakens the black pawn structure and brings a clear advantage. }
9... Qxd7 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. c4
{ Nc3 and Qh5 can follow, after which White decides whether O-O or O-O-O is safer, depending on the situation. }
*

