[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Queen's Pawn Countergambit, sometimes called the elephant gambit. Also not a particularly good choice for Black, but still with some pitfalls. At least in blitz chess it has found some strong supporters. }
3. exd5 Bd6
{ Black doesn't even think about getting the d5-pawn back. Instead, the plan is to seek counterplay with ...e5-e4, or the pawn mass e5 and f5 on the kingside and in the center.   White counters best directly in the center! }
4. d4 e4 5. Ne5
{ Now the knight has a good outpost and Black doesn't have enough compensation }
5... Nf6 6. Bb5+
{ The most direct and easiest way. No answer is satisfactory for Black. } 6...
c6 7. dxc6 { Of course we continue to capture and keep the pawn. } 7... bxc6 8.
Ba4 Bxe5
{ This looks interesting because it worsens the white king’s position, but Black still has problems. }
9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Ng4 11. Ke1
{ My favorite. On e2 you have to constantly think about ...Ba6+.   Black will then have problems developing the queenside because the c6-pawn needs protection. White still has to solve the problem of how to get the h1-rook into play, but Black’s problems will prove to be harder. }
11... Nxe5 12. Bf4 Ng6 13. Be3 f5 14. Nc3 Be6 15. Rd1
{ White is faster and already threatens with Rd6. } 15... Kf7 16. Ne2
{ Controls the square f4 and makes sure that f2-f3 cannot be followed by f5-f4 followed by e4-e3. }
16... Rc8 17. Nd4 Ne7 18. f3
{ White opens the position. This not only helps the bishops, but also makes it easy to bring the rook from h1 into play, e.g. Kf2 and Re1, or if the f-file opens, directly via f1. }
