1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Queen's Pawn Countergambit, sometimes called the elephant gambit. Also not a particularly good choice for Black, but still with some pitfalls. At least in blitz chess it has found some strong supporters. }
3. exd5 e4 { Here White has to be well prepared to gain an advantage. } 4. Qe2
Nf6 5. Nc3 Qe7 6. Ng5 Na6 7. Ngxe4 Nxe4 8. Qxe4
{ Easiest. We force the queen exchange and reduce the chances of counterplay. }
8... Qxe4+ 9. Nxe4 Nb4 10. Kd1
{ This might feel like a concession, but the king is safe here in the endgame. White is a pawn up and Black has no counterplay.   In the longer term, White can occupy the center with d4 and c3 and bring the king to c2. }
10... Nxd5 11. d4 Be6 12. c3 h6 13. Kc2
{ Next, the bishops and rooks can be brought into play. Moves like a2-a4 are also conceivable in order to expand on the queenside. }
