c6 7. dxc6
{ Why not take another pawn? We're not so far behind in development that it would be a cause for concern... }
7... Nxc6 8. Bb5
{ We don't necessarily want to win another pawn, but prepare the simple O-O. To do this, we prefer to move the bishop to an active square @@StartBracket@@b5@@EndBracket@@ instead of passively placing it on e2. }
8... Bd7
{ This requires a little caution because of potential deflections. We also don't want to simply capture on c6 after a7-a6, because the black bishop on c6 would aim very strongly against our kingside. }
9. c3 a6 10. Be2
{ An elegant solution: Black has no good moves.   10...Nd4  would be followed by  11.Qxd4  .  On slow moves White is ready to play Qd1 or d2-d4 and the white pawn center secures a winning position. }
