[Black "1C | Variation 2...Qe7 | 3...exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Qe7
{ This looks strange, but it's not so bad. As a rule, Black's plan here is to keep the position closed, which means that White's development advantage leads to nothing worthwhile.  After  3.d4  Black is ready to reply with  3...d6  , without  4.dxe5  dxe5  Qxd8+ being able to follow. Consequently, White can't really break through directly and has to play patiently.  In the following I show a plan how White can open the position in the long term. }
3. d4 exd4
{ This is not how Black usually plays. The more open the position, the more the misplaced the queen on e7 becomes. White is often prepared to sacrifice a pawn - sometimes even two - if lines open up in return. }
4. Be2 Qxe4 5. O-O
{ White is clearly better. Re1 follows with the threat of a deduction. White gets a big initiative for a single pawn @@StartBracket@@we will surely get the d4-pawn back@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Rare 2nd Moves after 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3"]
[Black "1C | Variation 2...Qe7 | 3...d6 / 8...a5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Qe7
{ This looks strange, but it's not so bad. As a rule, Black's plan here is to keep the position closed, which means that White's development advantage leads to nothing worthwhile.  After  3.d4  Black is ready to reply with  3...d6  , without  4.dxe5  dxe5  Qxd8+ being able to follow. Consequently, White can't really break through directly and has to play patiently.  In the following I show a plan how White can open the position in the long term. }
3. d4 d6 4. Nc3 Nf6 { Black prevents Nd5. } 5. Bc4
{ Development. The first threats with Ng5 and an attack on f7 are in the air. }
5... h6
{ 5...exd4  The opening of the position again only helps White. Black can't even capture the e4-pawn.  6.Nxd4  Nxe4?  7.Nd5  Qd8  8.Qe2  White will win material along the e-file. }
6. O-O c6
{ This is how Black usually plays. White has no quick and obvious way to open the position. But don't panic, Black also has no threats and a few problems of their own to solve.   In the meantime we can, for example, gain space on the queenside to create new weaknesses. }
7. a4
{ The pawn gains space, prevents b7-b5 and can sometimes advance even further. }
7... Bg4 8. Be3 a5
{ Black prevents further expansion with a4-a5, but also creates weaknesses on the queenside. }
9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nbd7
{ Black's strategy of keeping everything closed looks successful at first. However, White still has all the positional advantages, development, center, space, etc.   If Black brings the bishop to g7, the d6-pawn can quickly become weak. }
11. Qe2 g6 12. d5 Bg7 13. Rad1
{ White has a decisive advantage.   ➤ If Black captures on d5, White gets a perfect outpost. The d6-pawn can then be besieged.   ➤ If Black closes the position with ...c6-c5, the d5-pawn secures a permanent space advantage and the b5-square can be used for White's pieces.   ➤ If Black maintains the tension, White can capture on c6 themselves and then attack the d6-pawn with Qd2. }
*

