[Black "1D | Variation 2...Qf6 | 5...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Qf6 3. Nc3
{ White puts themselves in a position to chase the black queen. } 3... Nc6 4.
Nd5
{ I like this direct approach, Black has to return to d8 and White has brought the knight to d5 for free and can then open up the position. }
4... Qd8 5. d4 d6 6. Bg5
{ Even if Black tries to keep the position closed due to the development gap, we have a very direct solution at hand. }
6... Be7
{ 6...f6  7.Be3  . White has provoked a weakness and Black cannot undo the pawn move ...f7-f6. White is clearly better. }
7. Nxe7 Ngxe7 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+
{ White secures the bishop pair and wins more time because Black has to take with the king. }
9... Kxd8
{ 9...Nxd8?  costs a pawn.  10.Bxe7  . An important intermediate move, otherwise Nxe5 is followed by ...f7-f6 with a fork.  10...Kxe7  11.Nxe5+-  . White has a healthy pawn more and is clearly better. }
10. O-O-O+
{ White is better due to the pair of bishops and the fast development. Black still has to solve the problem of the king in the center in the long term - which is not easy because castling is no longer an option. }
