[Round "?"]
[White "2) Petrov 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nf6: Rare 3rd Moves "]
[Black "2A | Stafford Gambit 3...Nc6 | 4...dxc6 / 6...h5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov. It is considered one of the most solid openings for Black, but it does require accuracy. Another disadvantage for Black is that, if White wishes, it is possible to keep the game relatively symmetrical and minimize Black's chances of winning.  Nevertheless, we will try to find interesting, not necessarily symmetrical, ways to make life difficult for Black. We also try to keep the variations simple, as the Petrov is much less common than the main variations after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  . }
3. Nxe5
{ The main line. Alternatively, moves such as  3.Nc3  , with a transition to the Four Knights Game, or the forcing  3.d4  are also possible. }
3... Nc6
{ The Stafford Gambit. Not good, but tricky and quite popular in online chess. }
4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ This is the usual move, Black quickly opens all lines and diagonals for the pieces. Why is Black's game still doomed to failure? White has no weaknesses, and White also has two center pawns, the d-pawn and the e-pawn. These can - if used correctly - block the black piece play. }
5. d3 { White stabilizes the position. } 5... Bc5
{ Now ...Ng4 is threatened, but White can easily parry the threat. } 6. Be2 h5
{ A clever waiting move, ...Ng4 now becomes more attractive because after Bxg4 hxg4 the h-file would also open up. }
7. c3
{ Play in the center, White is ready to close the diagonal of the black bishop with d3-d4 and build up a strong center. }
7... Ng4 8. d4 Bb6
{ This is too slow and causes no problems. Black loses the initiative. } 9. h3
{ After a knight retreat the counterplay is absolutely over. Black has only one other attempt, but it fails tactically. }
9... Qh4 10. g3 { White wins material. } *

