[Black "2B | Petrov with 3...Nxe4 | 4...Qe7 / 5...f6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov. It is considered one of the most solid openings for Black, but it does require accuracy. Another disadvantage for Black is that, if White wishes, it is possible to keep the game relatively symmetrical and minimize Black's chances of winning.  Nevertheless, we will try to find interesting, not necessarily symmetrical, ways to make life difficult for Black. We also try to keep the variations simple, as the Petrov is much less common than the main variations after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  . }
3. Nxe5
{ The main line. Alternatively, moves such as  3.Nc3  , with a transition to the Four Knights Game, or the forcing  3.d4  are also possible. }
3... Nxe4 { is not recommended for Black, but not immediately lost either. } 4.
Qe2
{ White exploits the opposition on the e-file as well as the advantage to set up the first threats. Black must sacrifice a piece immediately, otherwise White wins the queen and the game. }
4... Qe7 5. Qxe4
{ White collects the material, but is prepared to give it back later @@StartBracket@@partially@@EndBracket@@ under good conditions. }
5... f6
{ This move is worse than  5...d6  , as Black weakens their king and does not prepare any development of the c8-bishop.  Our antidote remains similar: we can't save the knight and develop quickly while Black is still chasing material. }
6. d4 fxe5 7. Qxe5
{ White is a healthy pawn up, Black has no development advantage for the sacrificed material. White can complete the development with Bf4, Nc3 and O-O-O. }
7... Qxe5+ 8. dxe5 Nc6 9. Bf4
{ 9.f4?  The natural-looking f2-f4 is a typical mistake. White locks up the c1-bishop and Black still gets the desired development advantage after the strong  9...d6  .  d6⇆   Black opens the position and gets good compensation thanks to the active piece play. }
9... b6 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. O-O-O
{ White has a big advantage thanks to the extra pawn and the activity. Next, for example, Bc4 and Rhe1 can follow. }
*

