3... Nxe4 { is not recommended for Black, but not immediately lost either. } 4.
Qe2
{ White exploits the opposition on the e-file as well as the advantage to set up the first threats. Black must sacrifice a piece immediately, otherwise White wins the queen and the game. }
4... Qe7 5. Qxe4
{ White collects the material, but is prepared to give it back later @@StartBracket@@partially@@EndBracket@@ under good conditions. }
5... d6
{ Black immediately uses the pin on the e-file to win back the piece. In doing so, Black also clears the way for further pieces, here the bishop on c8.   5...Nc6?  6.d4  d6  is a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppppqppp/8/4N3/4Q3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  6.d4  Nc6  . }
6. d4 { White strengthens the center and prepares development. } 6... dxe5 7.
dxe5 Nc6 8. Nc3
{ The exclamation mark applies not only to the strength of the move, but also to its simplicity. White gives up the pawn and plays for activity. }
8... Qxe5 9. Qxe5+ Nxe5 10. Bf4
{ The bishop attacks the unprotected knight. It must be protected and cannot move itself, as the c7-pawn is unprotected. }
10... f6 11. O-O-O
{ White first continues their development and can later decide which plan they prefer. Depending on the black set-up, the following plans are available.   ➤ On set-ups with ...Bd6 White can weaken the black structure with Nb5 or Ne4 and fight for the bishop pair.   ➤ If Black does not move the bishop to d6 or withdraws it after an attack with Ne4, we change the pawn structure with Bxe5 fxe5 and get an outpost on e4. After that it is favorable for White to exchange light-squared bishops, after which a typical situation with a good knight against a bad bishop arises. }
11... Bd6 12. Bg3 a6 { Black prevents Nb5 with an attack on d6 and c7. } 13.
Ne4
{ In contrast to  13.Nb5  , the bishop can still move away here because c7 is not hanging. }
13... Be7
{ A simple plan. White converts the activity into a structural advantage, the knight on e4 is then huge and the e5-pawn tends to be weak. }
14. Bxe5 fxe5 15. Bc4 Bf5 16. Ng3 Bg6 17. h4 h5 18. Bd3
{ White wants to exchange the light-squared bishops and Black should evade. In any case, White can use the weak square e4 as a base for their own minor pieces. The e5-pawn remains permanently weak. }
