{ White improves their pieces with Re1, Nf1 or Ne5. Even though the situation may be objectively balanced, White has an easier game and Black must be more cautious due to the weakened position. }
12... O-O 13. Ne5
{ The black knight is hanging and if it is exchanged on e5, the rook gets thed5-pawn with a double attack.   13...Nb8?  is too passive. After  14.Ndf3  Nh4  15.Nxh4  Bxh4  16.Bf4  White was clearly better and went on to win in Nepomniachtchi, I – Lenderman, A, 2023. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Petrov: 3...d6 Sidelines 5th & 6th Move"]
[Black "3H | Petrov Sideline 6...Nc6 | 8...Nxd2 / 11...Bxf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov. It is considered one of the most solid openings for Black, but it does require accuracy. Another disadvantage for Black is that, if White wishes, it is possible to keep the game relatively symmetrical and minimize Black's chances of winning.  Nevertheless, we will try to find interesting, not necessarily symmetrical, ways to make life difficult for Black. We also try to keep the variations simple, as the Petrov is much less common than the main variations after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  . }
3. Nxe5
{ The main line. Alternatively, moves such as  3.Nc3  , with a transition to the Four Knights Game, or the forcing  3.d4  are also possible. }
3... d6
{ The normal move. Black first drives back the white knight and then wins back the pawn on e4. }
4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5
{ This is by far the most popular move. Black secures the knight and gains space in the center.  Other moves such as  5...Be7  or  5...Nf6  have no individual significance because Black will have to play ...d6-d5 sooner or later anyway. These moves are considered under the sequence  5...d5  6.Bd3  Be7  and  6...Nf6  respectively. }
6. Bd3
{ White develops the bishop to the most active square d3 - d3 is the best place for the bishop in many Petrov lines, as from there it takes part in the later fight for the outpost e4. At this point a number of possible setups and plans are available. }
6... Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2
{ We challenge the outpost on e4 and play without c2-c4 but mostly with c2-c3. This prevents the black knight from c6 from getting to b4 and after a possible Qb3 b7 also becomes vulnerable. Now Black has to decide what to do against the threat of Nxe4.   8.c4  . This is the old main variation and by far the most common move. If interested, the variation can be studied in more detail, but I recommend following the newer approach with 8. Nbd2. }
8... Nxd2 9. Bxd2 Bg4
{ 9...O-O  10.c3  Bg4  leads to the same result as the main line. } 10. c3
{ White is slightly more comfortable. The problem in the black position is the misplaced knight on c6 - if Black had a setup with knight on d7 and pawn on c6, everything would be balanced. In particular, Qb3 could then be answered with Qb6. In the current position, however, the question arises as to how Black...   ➤ 'activates' the knight,   ➤ reacts to a potential Qb3 @@StartBracket@@e.g. after h3 Bh5 g4@@EndBracket@@ }
10... O-O 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3
{ White gets the bishop pair and free play on the kingside and in the center. Next, the rooks can be activated or even more space can be won with g2-g3 and h3-h4-h5. White is clearly better. }
