9... Be7 10. Nc3 b6 11. Be3
{ An important detail. Although at first glance it may seem that the c5-pawn tends to be weak, on closer inspection Black cannot attack it so easily.   Moreover, the pawn further restricts the black pieces @@StartBracket@@control of d6@@EndBracket@@ and can be further stabilized, especially with b2-b4. }
11... bxc5 12. dxc5
{ The pawn structure has changed, but White has preserved the excellent square d4 for their knight @@StartBracket@@or bishop@@EndBracket@@. The knight is maximally stable there, as it can never be attacked by a black pawn.   Furthermore, a white knight exerts pressure against c6 @@StartBracket@@attack on the pawn if c7-c6 is played, otherwise simply Nc6 is threatened with a fork on bishop and queen@@EndBracket@@, but also has other squares like f5 available. }
12... Nbd7
{ Black attacks the c5-pawn, but White will be in time to implement the standard solution. }
13. b4 a5 14. a3
{ White has successfully secured the queenside pawn chain and Black is cramped. Once again, d4 is a perfect position for a white knight, where it is stable and looks deep into the opponent's camp. }
