[Black "4A | Petrov Main 6...Bd6 | 8...c6 / 9...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov. It is considered one of the most solid openings for Black, but it does require accuracy. Another disadvantage for Black is that, if White wishes, it is possible to keep the game relatively symmetrical and minimize Black's chances of winning.  Nevertheless, we will try to find interesting, not necessarily symmetrical, ways to make life difficult for Black. We also try to keep the variations simple, as the Petrov is much less common than the main variations after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  . }
3. Nxe5
{ The main line. Alternatively, moves such as  3.Nc3  , with a transition to the Four Knights Game, or the forcing  3.d4  are also possible. }
3... d6
{ The normal move. Black first drives back the white knight and then wins back the pawn on e4. }
4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5
{ This is by far the most popular move. Black secures the knight and gains space in the center.  Other moves such as  5...Be7  or  5...Nf6  have no individual significance because Black will have to play ...d6-d5 sooner or later anyway. These moves are considered under the sequence  5...d5  6.Bd3  Be7  and  6...Nf6  respectively. }
6. Bd3
{ White develops the bishop to the most active square d3 - d3 is the best place for the bishop in many Russian games, as from there it takes part in the later fight for the outpost e4. At this point there are a number of possible setups and plans available. }
6... Bd6
{ The most active way to develop the bishop. From here the bishop looks towards the white kingside and has its eye on the square e5. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Re1
{ The position we are aiming for. But why exactly do I think this position is a good practical solution for White, what advantages are there?   ➤ White has more space, which is particularly evident in the pawn pair c4 and c6. White exerts pressure on d5 and White will decide if and when to capture. In addition, White can also consider c4-c5 under good circumstances.   ➤ White threatens, Black reacts. White is always half a move ahead and so it is no surprise that White's threats come earlier. Black has to make many decisions early on.   Moving away from the general advantages, let's take a quick look at the most typical white plans in the given position.   ➤ Challenge the e4-outpost   ➤ Attack the weaknesses b7 and d5, this is usually done with Qb3 - a move that should be considered especially if Black has moved the c8-bishop and left b7 unprotected.   ➤ Transformation of the center structure: White is usually happy after Nc3 Nxc3 bxc3 because they get a more stable center due to the extra pawn on the c-file. The doubled pawn is also never permanent due to the tension c4-d5 and is therefore not a weakness. The operation also opens up the b-file, which will be useful for the white rook. }
9... Bf5 10. Qb3 Na6
{ Black thus indirectly prevents  11.Qxb7  which would now result in  11...Nb4  with a win for Black. White should rather play in the center and attack e4/d5. }
11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nc3 Nb4
{ The most active way. However, this approach requires sacrificing a pawn which you can't get back immediately.  12...Be6  13.a3  Nc7  − we've already seen this in the other move order. }
13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Bg5
{ A strong intermediate move that completes White's development. Note that f7-f6 is not possible here. }
14... Qb6
{ 14...Qe8?  , trying to defend the pawn only leads to poor coordination and White wins it back anyway...  15.Nh4!  ± The bishop has to go, White takes on e4 and is clearly better due to the extra pawn and the great activity. }
15. Nxe4 Be6 16. Qa3
{ The best place for the queen. Even if the situation looks dangerous because of the possible discovered attack, a closer look reveals that it is a pin. Moreover, the d6-bishop will soon be exchanged and the queen on a3 is no longer in danger. }
16... Rfe8 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. Bd2
{ Whether White has an advantage here can be debated, but in practice I would rather take White. We have several attempts to consolidate our extra pawn and Black has to be accurate to get counterplay. If you want to analyze further, you can look at both 19 Re5 and 19 Bxb4. }
