c6
{ The best choice. Black places their pawns so that they no longer have to worry about d5. The b8-knight can then be brought into play either via a6 to c7 or via d7. }
12. Bf4 Na6 13. Ne3 Re8 14. h4
{ White uses the development advantage to become active on the kingside first. Currently the pawn is untouchable because of  14...Bxh4  Nxh4  Qxh4  Bxd6  with a piece win.  If necessary, it can be protected with g2-g3. Also possible is h4-h5 to trap Black further, or even to establish a wedge pawn with h5-h6.  In addition, White controls the g5-square, which can be a good springboard for bishops or knights to set up threats against the black king. If Black takes on g5 in such a case, it is typical to take back with the h-pawn and use the h-file with the rooks after g2-g3 and Kg2. }
