[Black "5A | Philidor with 3...Nd7 | 4...c6 / 7...Nh6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 Nd7
{ Black tries to get into normal closed @@StartBracket@@i.e. without ...exd4@@EndBracket@@ Philidor positions, but it doesn't work with this move order. }
4. Bc4
{ More accurate than 4. Nc3. Black must now be very careful because threats with Ng5 or dxe5 and Qd5 are already in the air. The f7-point is, as so often, our target and very vulnerable. }
4... c6
{ The only move that maintains the tension and at the same time does not allow White to use any tactics. }
5. O-O Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Ng5
{ A strategic aim realised with tactical means. White temporarily sacrifices the knight in order to win the bishop pair. }
7... Nh6 8. Ne6
{ A nice tactical move, Black has to accept the sacrifice because the queen and the g7-pawn are hanging. White wins back the piece on h6 as Black cannot recapture, otherwise the king will be mated. }
8... fxe6 9. Bxh6 Bf8
{ After  9...gxh6??  10.Qh5+  Kf8  11.Bxe6  mate follows with Qf7 or Qxh6 in case of ...Qe8. }
10. Qh5+ g6 11. Qh3
{ White has a decisive positional advantage. Black has a weak double pawn, the c8-bishop doesn't come into play and castling isn't easy either. }
