{ This looks strange, but has a clear idea. After  7.exd6  Black can recapture with the bishop because it is not pinned on the g5-d8 diagonal. }
7. exd6 Bxd6 8. Nc3 Qe6+
{ Black tries to simplify, but White keeps up the tension. } 9. Be3 Qxd5 10.
Nxd5 { White threatens Bxc5 and then Nc7+ winning an exchange. } 10... Nbd7 11.
Nd2
{ White plays against the weakness on c7. Nc4 threatens to destroy the pawn structure and win the bishop pair. The bishop on d6 cannot escape because c7 is weak. }
11... c6 12. Nc4 Bb8 13. Nc3
{ Black has survived the direct attack without making any structural concessions, but now has to live with the strange positioning of the pieces... }
13... O-O 14. O-O-O Ne6 15. g3
{ White has several good continuations at their disposal. The knight can enter on d6 or the white-squared bishop can be developed to g2 or h3. }
