[Round "?"]
[White "5) Philidor: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 d6 "]
[Black "5C | Philidor with 3...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 Bg4
{ A bad move, known since the classic Morphy-Duke of Brunswick, Paris 1858. }
4. dxe5
{ Mandatory, Black cannot take on e5 because after the queen trade on d8 the e5-pawn would be lost. Black can only hold the pawn by exchanging on f3, but White gets the bishop pair plus a big initiative. }
4... Bxf3 5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4
{ White has a clear advantage, Qb3 can follow next, with a renewed attack on f7 and on b7.  Morphy's classic continued with:  6...Nf6  7.Qb3  Qe7  8.Nc3  c6  9.Bg5  b5  10.Nxb5  cxb5  11.Bxb5+  Nbd7  12.O-O-O  Rd8  13.Rxd7  Rxd7  14.Rd1  Qe6  15.Bxd7+  Nxd7  16.Qb8+  Nxb8  17.Rd8  , Morphy, P-Duke of Brunswick, C Paris 1858. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Philidor: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 d6 "]
[Black "5D | Philidor with 3...f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 { 3...Nc6  is a transposition to the chapter 'Alternatives on move 3'. }
3... f5
{ A rare and bad move. I would like to show a simple solution here, in which everything is quite forced... }
4. dxe5 fxe4 5. Ng5 d5
{ The only logical answer. Black stabilizes the center and covers e4. } 6. e6
{ White threatens a fork on f7 and the best advice for Black is already to sacrifice the exchange and hope for complications. In my opinion, however, the sacrifice is not frightening for White, but rather an act of desperation by Black. We take the material and are clearly better off. }
6... Nf6
{ After  6...Nh6  our knight remains anchored on g5 forever and so does the e6-pawn, which is a thorn in Black's side. White can continue with Nc3 and g3, Bh3 and further strengthen the e6-pawn, for example:  7.Nc3  c6  8.g3  Be7  9.Qh5++-  White has a strong attack and has a winning position. }
7. Nf7 Qe7 8. Nxh8 Bxe6 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Bb5
{ The black king wants to get to safety on the queenside, so White prepares to open up the position with Bxc6. }
10... O-O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ne2
{ White is clearly better. The h8-knight will be lost, but White still retains an extra exchange and has chances to attack on the queenside. }
*

