[White "5) Philidor: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 d6 "]
[Black "5E | Philidor with 3...exd4 | 7...c6 / 8...d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 exd4 { 3...Nc6  4.Bc4  transposes to chapter 6, see here. } 4. Nxd4 Nf6
5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bf4
{ White has a lot of alternatives at this point, like Be2, Bc4, Be3 and can then choose to castle long or short...   I recommend an active and sharp setup with Bf4, Qd2 and a quick O-O-O. The set-up is very universal, rarer than other set-ups, dangerous for Black and easy to remember. In the middlegame with unequal castling we often aim for a pawn storm with h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@and f2-f3, g2-g4@@EndBracket@@. }
6... O-O
{ Black can also start with  6...c6  ,  6...c5  ,  6...Nc6  . But since ...O-O is unavoidable, we will only consider this sequence. }
7. Qd2
{ Here we will study Black's most common and typical plans:  ➤  7...Nc6  with normal central piece play.   ➤  7...d5  , a direct attempt to break free.   ➤  7...c6  , a flexible waiting move preparing ...d6-d5.   ➤  7...a6  with the idea of getting activity on the wing with ...b7-b5. }
7... c6 8. O-O-O d5
{ This is not so popular, the position becomes symmetrical and White is slightly more active. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Kb1
{ White brings the bishop to f3 next and has the better minor pieces. Black cannot capture on g2 after Be2 as the attack on the g-file would be too dangerous. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Philidor: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 d6 "]
[Black "5E | Philidor with 3...exd4 | 7...c6 / 8...b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ With this move Black hints at playing the Philidor Defense. Black then, after  3.d4  , has the choice of opening the center with  3...exd4  or maintaining the tension with  3...Nd7  .  Black is slightly worse in both cases, but the open Philidor can sometimes quickly become sharp, while Black is often rather passive in the closed Philidor.  In addition, we will look at some less good attempts by Black,  3...Nc6  ,  3...Bg4?  ,  3...Nf6  or  3...f5?  - an idea of the inventor Philidor, which is nowadays considered refuted. }
3. d4 exd4 { 3...Nc6  4.Bc4  transposes to chapter 6, see here. } 4. Nxd4 Nf6
5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bf4
{ White has a lot of alternatives at this point, like Be2, Bc4, Be3 and can then choose to castle long or short...   I recommend an active and sharp setup with Bf4, Qd2 and a quick O-O-O. The set-up is very universal, rarer than other set-ups, dangerous for Black and easy to remember. In the middlegame with unequal castling we often aim for a pawn storm with h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@and f2-f3, g2-g4@@EndBracket@@. }
6... O-O
{ Black can also start with  6...c6  ,  6...c5  ,  6...Nc6  . But since ...O-O is unavoidable, we will only consider this sequence. }
7. Qd2
{ Here we will study Black's most common and typical plans:  ➤  7...Nc6  with normal central piece play.   ➤  7...d5  , a direct attempt to break free.   ➤  7...c6  , a flexible waiting move preparing ...d6-d5.   ➤  7...a6  with the idea of getting activity on the wing with ...b7-b5. }
7... c6 8. O-O-O b5
{ This is how Black usually plays, hoping for counterplay on the queenside and in the center. Now ... b5-b4 threatens to win the e4-pawn. }
9. f3
{ White stabilizes the e4-pawn, but at the same time becomes ready for g2-g4! }
9... b4
{ 9...a5  costs too much time and does not lead to the desired goal of opening the position.  10.g4  a4  11.Nce2!  , White is almost winning, the knights are on their way to f5, while Black can't even play b5-b4.  ...a4-a3 is always followed by b2-b3 and the queenside remains closed. The computer already suggests  11...Qa5  , but the endgame is terrible for Black. }
10. Na4 { A strong move after which White gains a huge advantage. } 10... Qa5
11. b3 Rd8 { Black first covers d6 before c6-c5 and ... Bd7 follow. } 12. g4
{ White prepares a strong outpost for the knight on f5. } 12... c5 13. Nf5 Bxf5
14. gxf5
{ White has successfully opened the g-file and ...Bd7 is no longer to be feared. Let's look at the other possibility to eliminate the knight on a4: Nb8-d7-b6. }
14... Nbd7 15. Rg1 Nb6 16. Kb1
{ The same motive as in the variations after ... Bd7. White sacrifices the b-pawn, but after that Black already has no more threats! }
16... Nxa4 17. bxa4 Qxa4 18. Bc4
{ The black attack comes to an end and White is ready for the counter-attack. White is winning. }
