{ White has a lot of alternatives at this point, like Be2, Bc4, Be3 and can then choose to castle long or short...   I recommend an active and sharp setup with Bf4, Qd2 and a quick O-O-O. The set-up is very universal, rarer than other set-ups, dangerous for Black and easy to remember. In the middlegame with unequal castling we often aim for a pawn storm with h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@and f2-f3, g2-g4@@EndBracket@@. }
6... O-O
{ Black can also start with  6...c6  ,  6...c5  ,  6...Nc6  . But since ...O-O is unavoidable, we will only consider this sequence. }
7. Qd2
{ Here we will study Black's most common and typical plans:  ➤  7...Nc6  with normal central piece play.   ➤  7...d5  , a direct attempt to break free.   ➤  7...c6  , a flexible waiting move preparing ...d6-d5.   ➤  7...a6  with the idea of getting activity on the wing with ...b7-b5. }
7... a6 8. O-O-O Re8 9. h4 b5 10. f3
{ White's attack is faster, Black could advance with ...b5-b4, but has no pieces nearby to support the attack.   White is superior both in the center @@StartBracket@@Nc3-d5 ideas are possible@@EndBracket@@ and on the kingside h4-h5-h6 @@StartBracket@@possibly also in combination with g4-g5-g6@@EndBracket@@. }
*

