1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... d6
{ A passive move that develops nothing. We remain true to our basic principle against such approaches: we open the position as quickly as possible. }
4. d4 Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 Nf6 { 6...Nxd4??  7.Qxf7#  . } 7. d5 Ne7 8. Be3
Nd7 9. Nd2 g6 10. g4
{ White has a space advantage and the bishop pair.   The advance ... f7-f5 is not to be feared: White can capture twice and then gets the excellent e4-square for the knight. In addition, ...f7-f5 means an opening of the g-file, which also benefits White because their own king is on the queenside while the lines around the black king open up. }
