[Black "6A | Italian with 3...d6 | 4...Nf6 / 6...Nxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... d6
{ A passive move that develops nothing. We remain true to our basic principle against such approaches: we open the position as quickly as possible. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Ng5
{ A direct attack against the f7-point, Black must now find a series of precise moves to avoid losing immediately. }
5... d5 6. exd5 Nxd4
{ 6...Nxd5  leads to a bad variation from the Fried-Liver attack, with the addition that White has an extra move. Black is lost. }
7. c3 b5
{ The counter-attack is answered with a typical retreat, which we will see more often in chapter 11. }
8. Bf1
{ Saves the bishop and avoids its exchange. After a retreat of the knight from d4, the pawn on b5 will fall and White will be better off. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Italian: Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "6A | Italian with 3...d6 | 4...Nf6 / 6...Nxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... d6
{ A passive move that develops nothing. We remain true to our basic principle against such approaches: we open the position as quickly as possible. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Ng5
{ A direct attack against the f7-point, Black must now find a series of precise moves to avoid losing immediately. }
5... d5 6. exd5 Nxd4
{ 6...Nxd5  leads to a bad variation from the Fried-Liver attack, with the addition that White has an extra move. Black is lost. }
7. c3 Nf5 8. d6 Nxd6
{ The most natural reply, Black eliminates the pawn and at the same time protects the pawn on f7. }
9. Nxf7
{ A surprising blow! Black can't take back twice, otherwise the queen on d8 will be lost. }
9... Qe7
{ A mistake that loses the game. The queen would be better on d7, from where it controls the diagonal a4-e8. }
10. Nxh8
{ Here we can capture the rook, even if Black will take on c4 and our knight remains trapped in the corner. }
10... Nxc4 11. Qa4+
{ The key. We directly win back the knight on c4 and remain with extra exchange, even if Black captures the knight from h8. }
*

