[Black "6A | Italian with 3...d6 | 4...Nf6 / 6...Nxd4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... d6
{ A passive move that develops nothing. We remain true to our basic principle against such approaches: we open the position as quickly as possible. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Ng5
{ A direct attack against the f7-point, Black must now find a series of precise moves to avoid losing immediately. }
5... d5 6. exd5 Nxd4
{ 6...Nxd5  leads to a bad variation from the Fried-Liver attack, with the addition that White has an extra move. Black is lost. }
7. c3 Nf5 8. d6 Nxd6
{ The most natural reply, Black eliminates the pawn and at the same time protects the pawn on f7. }
9. Nxf7
{ A surprising blow! Black can't take back twice, otherwise the queen on d8 will be lost. }
9... Qd7 10. Nxd6+
{ 10.Nxh8?  with the black queen on d7 would be a big mistake. Black will capture on c4 and in the long run capture h8. After that White has a material disadvantage.  10...Nxc4-+  , White cannot win the c4-knight here with Qa4+ because the black queen controls a4. }
10... Bxd6 11. O-O
{ Even though the position here is balanced, I would prefer White. Black has the worse pawn structure and can't castle so easily. }
