{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... h6
{ The idea of the move is to play ...Nf6 next, without having to worry about Ng5. However, ...h6 is a bad move because Black loses too much time.   Our antidote to such slow moves is always the same: open the position. In an open position, a development advantage will always be more noticeable than in a closed one.   In a closed position there is no direct confrontation and the extra piece does not come into its own. If the position is open, it usually becomes concrete and threats arise. One or two additionally developed pieces can make all the difference. }
4. d4
{ The center opens and White threatens dxe5. In contrast to moves like  4.O-O  or  4.Nc3  , Black's room for error is much smaller and another bad move can cost them the game. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6
{ ➤  5...Nxd4?  is a strategic mistake. White can now centralize the queen with  6.Qxd4  and Black can no longer chase it away with ...Nc6.  6...c5  can simply be answered with  7.Qd3  and Black would only have weakened themselves. Otherwise the white queen remains in its powerful position in the center.     ➤  5...Ne5?!  , Black loses time with the second move with the same piece. White also has to move the bishop again with  6.Be2±  , but can later occupy the center with tempo by f2-f4. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Nc3 Bb4
{ 7...Bd6  is the computer's suggestion to prevent the disturbing e4-e5. However, the bishop on d6 is in a bad position because it prevents the development with ...d7-d6. White has several good continuations, such as  8.Qf3  ,  8.Qd3  or  8.Be3  . }
8. e5 { The sharpest attempt, Black must now act very precisely. } 8... Ne4
{ The most frequent attempt, but White can afford to ignore the threats and continue their own initiative. }
9. Qg4 { Attack against e4 and g7. Now there is no turning back for Black. }
9... Nxc3 10. Qxg7 Ne4+ 11. c3
{ All knight moves are treated analogously: c2-c3 and Black cannot save rook and bishop at the same time, White wins back the material with interest. }
