9. Qg4 { Attack against e4 and g7. Now there is no turning back for Black. }
9... Nxc3 10. Qxg7 Rf8 11. a3
{ A strong intermediate move whose logic we should understand exactly: The black bishop is optimally positioned on b4. For one thing, it covers the rook on f8, which becomes important after a white Bxh6, for example.  In addition, the bishop is within reach of its own knight. Thus the pin  11.Bd2  doesn't work because Black covers the bishop with  12...Nd5  and saves both knight and bishop. }
