[White "6) Italian: Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "6C | Italian with 3...Nd4 | 6...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... Nd4
{ A well-known opening trap. We just have to remember that we can't capture on e5, because otherwise Black gets a dangerous double attack against e5 and g2 after  4.Nxe5  Qg5  .  Apart from the trap, 3...Nd4 is not good - Black moves an already developed piece again and thus gets behind in development. }
4. Nxd4
{ Simple and strong. We exchange the central knight - the only developed black piece.   4.Nxe5??  − you shouldn't react like this.  4...Qg5  5.Nxf7?  . Consistent, but wrong. After the capture on g2, Black will win more material than White or even mate.  5...Qxg2  6.Rf1  Qxe4+  . Now White must give up the queen, otherwise a nice mate will follow.  7.Be2  Nf3#  . }
4... exd4 5. O-O Nf6 6. d3 Bc5 { This active move is directly refuted. } 7. e5
d5
{ The normal reply to e4-e5, but here the concrete details don't work for Black. In particular, the g7-pawn is unprotected, so that White can simply force their way through. }
8. exf6 dxc4 9. fxg7 Rg8 10. Qh5
{ The double attack on the h7-pawn and the c5-bishop decides the game. } *

