1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... g6
{ Black wants to fianchetto the bishop on g7 and play a King's Indian setup. However, White again comes first with the play in the center. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. O-O
{ White naturally develops further. Black must now decide how to get the knight into play. }
7... d6 8. Nc3 Ne7
{ Here we have a simple and effective plan at our disposal: The exchange of the bishop on g7. This creates weaknesses on the black squares around the black king and makes the white position easier to play; an attack against the king with f2-f4-f5 is also conceivable. }
9. Be3 O-O 10. Bd4
{ Our strategic goal is achieved, the strong bishop on g7 is exchanged. Otherwise Black has to lock up their own bishop with ...f7-f6. }
