1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... f5
{ Similar to the Jähnisch Gambit against the Spanish. In the Italian opening, however, this early advance of the f-pawn works much worse. The white bishop is better on c4 here than on b5 in the Spanish. The weak a2-g8 diagonal is immediately under attack. }
4. d4
{ We are better developed and open the center again. Black has now tried three different moves }
4... fxe4 5. Nxe5 d5 6. Bb5
{ White saves the bishop and now threatens both Nxc6 and Qh5+. Black must try to prevent both.  Not  6.Qh5+?  . White must not ignore Black's counter-threats.  6...g6  7.Nxg6  Nf6  8.Qh4  Nxd4!  and Black stands to win. }
6... Qf6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Qxd5
{ A nice cross-pin, the queen cannot be captured. If the bishop is captured, Black loses the rook. If Black protects c6, the white queen can save itself with a gain of time. }
9... Bd7 10. Qxe4+ { White remains with an extra pawn and a winning position. }
