[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... Be7
{ The Hungarian Defense. Black develops and prevents sharp variations such as  3...Bc5  4.d4  or  4.b4  as well as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Ng5  . However, this also has its price, the bishop on e7 is too passive to pose problems for White. }
4. d4
{ Due to Black's passive play we have the freedom to open the center and use this opportunity immediately. }
4... exd4
{ This leads to a kind of 'Scottish game, in which White has the extra move Bc4 and Black ...Be7 - which in my opinion only benefits White. The e7-bishop is passive and may have to move again.   Nevertheless, the black position is solid and White is only a little better. }
5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O d6
{ White has many liberties in such positions. The position can be strengthened with h3, Bf4, Qd2 and centralization of the rooks. After that, White often breaks up the position with a well-timed e4-e5 }
8. h3
{ This prevents all ideas with ...Bg4, which will prove to be very useful. Let's look at a direct attempt by Black. @@StartBracket@@Otherwise we stick to our general development scheme.@@EndBracket@@ }
8... Ne5 9. Bb3 { Don't be afraid of ...c5-c4! } 9... c5 10. Nf3
{ Now Black cannot pin with ...Bg4. } 10... c4
{ Forced, otherwise the operation makes no sense. } 11. Nxe5 cxb3 12. Nf3
{ White is better. In the resulting middlegame the d6-pawn can be permanently besieged. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Italian: Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "6H | Italian with 3...Be7 | 4...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4, from where it is eyeing the square f7.  In this chapter we will look at all of Black's replies except  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... Be7
{ The Hungarian Defense. Black develops and prevents sharp variations such as  3...Bc5  4.d4  or  4.b4  as well as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Ng5  . However, this also has its price, the bishop on e7 is too passive to pose problems for White. }
4. d4
{ Due to Black's passive play we have the freedom to open the center and use this opportunity immediately. }
4... d6
{ This is now possible because after  5.dxe5  dxe5  the bishop on d8 can also take back. }
5. dxe5
{ A simple move compared to the alternative d4-d5. We get an endgame in which we have a small initiative with the better development and at the same time avoid a lot of theory. }
5... dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Bxd8
{ Black naturally captures with the bishop, the alternatives are clearly worse.  6...Nxd8  loses the e5-pawn, while  6...Kxd8  gives up the castling right. }
7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Be3 { With a small advantage due to the more active bishops. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Italian: 3...Bc5 4.d4 Nxd4"]
[Black "7 | Italian with 4...Nxd4 | 5...d5 / 6...Be6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Nxd4
{ A rare but good move. In my opinion, it is rarely seen in practice for two reasons:  1@@EndBracket@@ Black must react to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  with  3...exd4  . Our move order is rarer and it's not worth it for Black studying another reply.  2@@EndBracket@@ After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/8/2b1p3/2BnP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxe5  , Black has to play  5...Qe7  and allow themselves to be captured on f7, then play further accurate moves, which many players find impractical in a minor variation. }
5. Nxe5
{ My recommendation and true to our approach of playing aggressive variations. Black has only one good reply and only found it in about 25% of the games played. On all other replies White gets a big or decisive advantage.  Unlike in the Blackburne Gambit, after 4.d4 Black doesn't have the option to play ...Qg5 here. }
5... d5 6. Bxd5
{ We take with the bishop and ask the same question again. How does Black defend f7?  White already has one more healthy pawn and doesn't necessarily have to get involved in complications, but can bring the king to safety with an early O-O and complete the development.  After all, Black can now play  6...Be6  or  6...Ne6  because they could take back with the bishop. }
6... Be6 7. c3 Bxd5 8. cxd4 Bb4+ { This does not save the bishop. } 9. Ke2 Bxe4
10. Qa4+ { Double attack. White wins a piece. } *

