5. Nxe5
{ My recommendation and true to our approach of playing aggressive variations. Black has only one good reply and only found it in about 25% of the games played. On all other replies White gets a big or decisive advantage.  Unlike in the Blackburne Gambit, after 4.d4 Black doesn't have the option to play ...Qg5 here. }
5... d6 6. Nxf7 Qh4 7. O-O
{ Bring the king to safety. The rook on h8 does not run away. Black now has two attempts:  ➤  7...b5  to destabilise the bishop who is guarding the f7-knight.  ➤  7...Bg4  with initiative on the kingside.  @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/ppp2Npp/3p4/2b5/2BnP2q/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nxh8?  , White should not be too greedy, otherwise Black will get counterplay:  7...Bg4  8.Qd2  Bf3!  with complications. Our solution is much simpler. }
7... Bg4 8. Qd2 b5 9. c3
{ White wins after this counter-attack. Black cannot maintain the threats. } *

