{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Nxd4
{ A rare but good move. In my opinion, it is rarely seen in practice for two reasons:  1@@EndBracket@@ Black must react to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  with  3...exd4  . Our move order is rarer and it's not worth it for Black studying another reply.  2@@EndBracket@@ After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/8/2b1p3/2BnP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxe5  , Black has to play  5...Qe7  and allow themselves to be captured on f7, then play further accurate moves, which many players find impractical in a minor variation. }
5. Nxe5
{ My recommendation and true to our approach of playing aggressive variations. Black has only one good reply and only found it in about 25% of the games played. On all other replies White gets a big or decisive advantage.  Unlike in the Blackburne Gambit, after 4.d4 Black doesn't have the option to play ...Qg5 here. }
5... Qe7
{ The best and only defence. Without experience or theoretical knowledge, however, such a move is very difficult to find.  Black doesn't prevent the capture on f7, but attacks our knight. But why exactly 5...Qe7 and not  5...Qf6?  We will look at these differences and all other black defensive attempts in the following. }
6. Bxf7+ Kf8 7. Bxg8 Kxg8 8. Ng4
{ 8.Nc4  Qxe4+  9.e3  would be a transposition. } 8... Qxe4+ 9. Ne3 b6 10. Nc3
{ Certainly not my favorite position, but Black can't really count on an advantage yet. Moreover, the line is the best Black can do and the way up to here has never been found in practice. }
10... Qe5 11. O-O Ba6 12. Re1 Re8 13. Bd2
{ White finishes the development and protects the e1-rook. Now discoveries on the e-file are in the air. }
13... Re6 14. Ng4 Qf5 15. Rxe6 Nxe6 16. Ne3 Qf7 17. Ne4 Bf8 18. c4
{ Even if Black has absolutely no problems here from an objective point of view, the position is playable for both sides. After all, Black still has to solve the strange position of the king - not an ordinary task and certainly with the potential for mistakes }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Italian: 3...Bc5 4.d4 Bxd4, Other 5th & 6th Moves"]
[Black "8A | Italian with 5...exd4 | 6...Nf6 / 11...Qd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Bxd4
{ In this chapter we take a closer look at the move 4...Bxd4. Bxd4 is the second most popular move and a good answer. }
5. Nxd4 exd4
{ This also temporarily wins a pawn, but Black weakens the pawn structure for no reason - d4 becomes a permanent weakness.   We can therefore slowly but surely try to collect the d4-pawn with Nd2-f3 or Nd2-b3. If we succeed, we have an advantage: While material is level we have two bishops and a space advantage in the centre. }
6. O-O Nf6 7. e5 d5
{ ➤  7...Ne4??  8.Qg4+-  and White wins through the double attack on the knight and the g7-pawn.     ➤  7...Nxe5?  8.Re1  d6  9.f4+-  winning a piece. }
8. exf6 dxc4 9. fxg7
{ The most accurate move order.  In case of  9.Re1+  Black could in addition to 9...Be6 answer with  9...Kf8  and that can be avoided with our move order. }
9... Rg8 10. Re1+ Be6 11. Qh5
{ An important detail. White threatens Rxe6 as well as Qxh7, keeping the initiative going. }
11... Qd7 12. Qxh7 O-O-O 13. Bg5
{ White tries to cement the g-pawn with Bf6 and thwarts Black's idea of eliminating the pawn with f7-f5 and Qxg7.   13.Bh6??  is of course impossible because of  13...Bf5  and the white queen is trapped. }
13... Rde8 14. Bf6
{ White is winning, but we still look at how Black could seek counterplay. }
14... Nb4 { Black wants to challenge our f6-bishop with Nd5. } 15. Nd2 Nd5
{ 15...Nxc2??  16.Qxc2+-  with an extra piece for White. } 16. Qh6 Nxf6 17.
Qxf6
{ The position remains complex, but White already has a decisive advantage. The queen on f6 is fantastic and the dangerous g7-pawn remains alive. The black centre soon comes under attack, e.g. after Rad1 and Nf3.   If Black opens the position with ...d4-d3, the white rooks benefit more as the black ones are busy with the g7-pawn. }
*

