{ In this chapter we take a closer look at the move 4...Bxd4. Bxd4 is the second most popular move and a good answer. }
5. Nxd4 exd4
{ This also temporarily wins a pawn, but Black weakens the pawn structure for no reason - d4 becomes a permanent weakness.   We can therefore slowly but surely try to collect the d4-pawn with Nd2-f3 or Nd2-b3. If we succeed, we have an advantage: While material is level we have two bishops and a space advantage in the centre. }
6. O-O d6 7. c3
{ 7.Nd2?!  is not so precise here because - in contrast to the variation with 6...Nge7 - Black is already ready for  7...Be6  . After  8.Bxe6  fxe6  we wouldn't be ready for the exchange with Nxd4. }
7... Nf6 8. cxd4 O-O 9. Nc3
{ Covering e4 and threatening to keep a strong centre permanently after Bb3. Black must act tactically immediately as long as the bishop is still on c4. }
9... Nxe4 10. Nxe4 d5
{ Black has split the centre and wins back the piece. With precise play, however, White holds out hope of an advantage. }
11. Bg5 Qd7 12. Nc5 Qf5 13. Bb5
{ We prepare an advantageous exchange. Black has no choice and still has to recapture the piece on g5. }
13... Qxg5 14. Bxc6 bxc6
{ We have reached a position in which it is not noticeable that Black is a pawn up. }
15. Qc1 Qxc1 16. Raxc1
{ The knight will dominate the bishop in the long run and can later attack Black's weaknesses. White is better }
