1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Bxd4
{ In this chapter we take a closer look at the move 4...Bxd4. Bxd4 is the second most popular move and a good answer. }
5. Nxd4 exd4
{ This also temporarily wins a pawn, but Black weakens the pawn structure for no reason - d4 becomes a permanent weakness.   We can therefore slowly but surely try to collect the d4-pawn with Nd2-f3 or Nd2-b3. If we succeed, we have an advantage: While material is level we have two bishops and a space advantage in the centre. }
6. O-O d6 7. c3
{ 7.Nd2?!  is not so precise here because - in contrast to the variation with 6...Nge7 - Black is already ready for  7...Be6  . After  8.Bxe6  fxe6  we wouldn't be ready for the exchange with Nxd4. }
7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 Nf6 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4
{ White maintains the pin. Black should not weaken their position with ...g7-g5. }
10... Ne5
{ The best attempt to get rid of the pin. Black attacks the bishop on c4 and after its retreat plans to ask the pinning bishop with ...Ng6. However, White has a dynamic solution at hand. }
11. f4 Nxc4 { White wins the piece back immediately. } 12. Qa4+ c6 13. Qxc4
{ White still has pressure against f6 and Black has a very hard time ever getting rid of the pin without allowing the weakening of the pawn structure after Bxf6 gxf6. }
