5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Be3
{ A relatively unexplored idea. White confronts Black with a difficult question: should you try to keep the extra pawn or should you try to finish the development quickly instead?   6.O-O  is the 'normal' way for White. White goes for quick development and tries to open the position with f2-f4, f4xe5 and Bg5.  6...Nf6  7.f4  d6  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.Bg5  . However, this approach has already been tried in more than 1000 games and, in my opinion, can neither surprise Black nor pose any serious problems. }
6... Qf6 7. Nc3 Ne7 { Otherwise Nd5 comes with tempo. } 8. f4
{ White undermines the outpost on d4. Black has big problems because the central outpost can no longer be maintained. }
8... Ne6 { After  8...exf4??  9.Bxd4+-  White wins a piece. } 9. f5 Nd4 10. O-O
{ White has a big advantage. Black has concrete problems to finish the development and must always expect that White will increase the pressure on d4 with Dd2 and Tad1 or start actions on the kingside with Dh5, Lg5 and f5-f6.   10...O-O?  11.Qh5  h6  12.g4!  . The conditions for a wing attack are ideal: Closed centre and few black defenders.  12...b5   @@StartBracket@@  12...Nxc2?  , the hunt for material comes too late and White simply continues to attack, e.g.  13.g5  Qd6  14.Rad1  Qb4  15.gxh6  Nxe3  16.hxg7  Kxg7  17.f6+  and White mates.@@EndBracket@@  13.Bd5  c6  14.g5!  . White begins to chase the blocking queen away from f6 and then follows up with f5-f6 with a decisive attack.  14...hxg5  15.Bxg5  Qd6  16.Bxe7  Qxe7  17.f6+-  . White gets either an open g-file or attacking chances with a wedge pawn on f6 and Qg5-g7#. }
