{ This avoids the fight. Black doesn't try to hold on to the extra pawn and simply wants to develop.   However, this gives White a free hand in the centre, wins back the pawn and White is in a better position thanks to the better piece activity and the space advantage. }
7. Bxd4 exd4 8. Qxd4 { 8.e5?!  allows a typical counterattack.  8...d5!  . }
8... O-O 9. Nc3 { 9.e5?!  still allows the typical counterattack  9...d5! = }
9... d5
{ This is a direct attempt to open the centre and punish the position of the white king on e1. However, White gladly accepts the challenge and retains a clear advantage. }
10. exd5 Re8+ 11. Be2 Be6
{ Black uses the pin on the d-file to win back the pawn immediately. } 12. d6
{ A typical motive. White worsens the black pawn structure and can besiege the isolated pawn in the following middlegame. White has a long-term strategic advantage.   12.O-O-O ?  gives away the advantage because the bishop on e2 loses its protection. Black wins back the pawn on d5.  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  14.Qxd5  Bxd5  15.Rxd5  Rxe2=  , the rook ending is equal. }
12... cxd6 13. O-O-O Qa5 14. a3
{ 14.Kb1  fails to  14...Bxa2+  because the knight is overloaded with the protection of a2 and e2. }
14... h6 15. h4
{ With an advantage for White. It should be noted here that White should be in no hurry to capture the d6-pawn. The pawn remains weak into the endgame and even restricts Black's piece activity @@StartBracket@@our queen can remain undisturbed on the excellent d4-square@@EndBracket@@.   All this gives White a positional advantage and the better piece play. Of course, White can eventually consider winning the pawn, but must always keep an eye on potential counterplay. }
