3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Bxd4
{ In this chapter we take a closer look at the move 4...Bxd4. Bxd4 is the second most popular move and a good answer. }
5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Be3
{ A relatively unexplored idea. White confronts Black with a difficult question: should you try to keep the extra pawn or should you try to finish the development quickly instead?   6.O-O  is the 'normal' way for White. White goes for quick development and tries to open the position with f2-f4, f4xe5 and Bg5.  6...Nf6  7.f4  d6  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.Bg5  . However, this approach has already been tried in more than 1000 games and, in my opinion, can neither surprise Black nor pose any serious problems. }
6... Ne6
{ At first glance this looks very logical. Black covers the weak point g7 and keeps the squares d4 and f4 under control. However, White has a surprising solution which achieves a small advantage. }
7. Bxe6
{ An exchange which we only carry out for concrete reasons. White exchanges their opponent's only developed piece and then aims for the weak point g7 - an idea which we will encounter again and again. }
7... dxe6 8. Qh5
{ Black must now decide whether to defend the extra pawn or give it back in favour of a quick development. }
8... Qf6 9. Nc3 a6
{ ➤  9...Ne7??  10.Nb5+-  , Black loses material.  ➤  9...c6?  prevents the white threat Nb5, but traps the c8-bishop permanently.  10.O-O-O  . White is positionally winning. }
10. O-O-O Bd7 11. Rd2
{ White increases the pressure on the d-file. Black is not yet ready for  11...O-O-O  because of  12.Bg5  . }
11... Ne7 12. Rhd1 Bc6 13. g4
{ White protects their queen so that after Bg5 Qg6 the knight on e7 can be captured. Black has problems finishing the development. }
13... O-O 14. Bg5 Qg6 15. Bxe7 { White is a piece up and wins. } *

