3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... Bxd4
{ In this chapter we take a closer look at the move 4...Bxd4. Bxd4 is the second most popular move and a good answer. }
5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Be3
{ A relatively unexplored idea. White confronts Black with a difficult question: should you try to keep the extra pawn or should you try to finish the development quickly instead?   6.O-O  is the 'normal' way for White. White goes for quick development and tries to open the position with f2-f4, f4xe5 and Bg5.  6...Nf6  7.f4  d6  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.Bg5  . However, this approach has already been tried in more than 1000 games and, in my opinion, can neither surprise Black nor pose any serious problems. }
6... Nc6
{ The most popular reply. Black secures the knight and extra pawn.  However, White has two active bishops and can now target the weak points f7 or g7 with the queen. Both moves,  7.Qh5  and  7.Qg4  allow Black to equalise, but there are some difficulties to overcome on the way. }
7. Qg4 Qf6
{ This has been played almost exclusively so far. Black protects g7 without irreversibly weakening the structure with ...g7-g6 and sets up the threat ... d7-d5 winning a piece. }
8. Nc3
{ Provocative, but strong! What do you think White has planned after the discovered attack with  8...d5 ? }
8... d5
{ A tempting move which happened in the majority of games. However, White has a Quiet but strong reply which Black can easily overlook. }
9. Qg3 dxc4
{ Now there is no way back, otherwise Black simply loses the pawn on d5 while White keeps the development advantage on top. }
10. Nd5 Qg6
{ Black must keep the g7-pawn defended, otherwise a whole rook will be lost after Qxg7. Giving up the a8-rook is the better attempt to hold the position. In that case, Black does at least have the hope of trapping the white knight in the corner. }
11. Nxc7+ Kd8 12. Nxa8
{ The position is already won for White here, but it is worth taking a closer look at a few tactical ideas. Black has several ideas to capture the knight, but none of them work. }
12... Qxg3
{ Black's best bet is to exchange queens. Otherwise, the white queen often becomes active and the black king comes under attack. }
13. O-O-O+
{ It is important to give the check before Black has cleared the c8-square for the king.   13.hxg3?!  Be6  14.O-O-O+ ?  Kc8!  would be anything but clear. }
13... Bd7 14. fxg3
{ An important nuance: the rook can now quickly enter the game via the f-file. This opens up too many fronts and it becomes impossible for Black to trap the knight in the corner.   14.hxg3  Nf6  is also better for White but less convincing. }
14... Kc8 { This is too direct and costs further material. } 15. Bxa7 Nxa7 16.
Nb6+ Kc7 17. Nxd7 { White has a decisive material advantage. } *

