11. Nxc7+ Kd8 12. Nxa8
{ The position is already won for White here, but it is worth taking a closer look at a few tactical ideas. Black has several ideas to capture the knight, but none of them work. }
12... Qxg3
{ Black's best bet is to exchange queens. Otherwise, the white queen often becomes active and the black king comes under attack. }
13. O-O-O+
{ It is important to give the check before Black has cleared the c8-square for the king.   13.hxg3?!  Be6  14.O-O-O+ ?  Kc8!  would be anything but clear. }
13... Bd7 14. fxg3
{ An important nuance: the rook can now quickly enter the game via the f-file. This opens up too many fronts and it becomes impossible for Black to trap the knight in the corner.   14.hxg3  Nf6  is also better for White but less convincing. }
14... Nf6
{ The primary difficulty in picking up the knight with ...Kc8-b8 is the unprotected bishop on d7. This is shown, for example, by the variation  14...Kc8  15.Bxa7  Nxa7  and  16.Nb6  with a double attack and material gain for White.  It is therefore first necessary to cover the bishop on d7 with the help of 14...Nf6 in order to be able to continue with ...Kc8.  In the case of fxg3, however, this doesn't work because the white rook will soon eliminate the knight on f6. }
15. Rhf1
{ Our key move. Black cannot parry the threatened exchange sacrifice. } 15...
Kc8 16. Bxa7 Nxa7 17. Rxf6 { Now the d7-bishop is only protected once. } 17...
gxf6 18. Nb6+
{ White wins, we have an extra pawn plus Black has further weaknesses on c4 and f6. }
*

