8. Nxf7 Nxf7 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. cxb4 Qf6 11. O-O
{ Objectively the strongest continuation. The rook on a1 is untouchable because of  11...Qxa1  12.Qb3+  --  and  13.Bb2+  trapping the enemy queen.  @@StartFEN@@r1b3nr/pppp1kpp/5q2/8/1P2P3/8/P4PPP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qb3+  Qe6  − the queen exchange would help Black because the black king is more open than their white opponent. We therefore prefer to keep the queens on the board. }
11... d6 { Black prepares to counterattack  12.Qb3+  with  12...Be6  . } 12.
Qc2
{ White attacks the weak point c7 and prepares Bb2. Black still can't take the rook. }
12... Qxa1 13. Nc3
{ White protects a2 and follows up with Bb2 or Bg5. Black can then capture with the queen on f1 and maintain the material balance, but still has big problems: The rooks remain passive and White can attack weaknesses such as c7 or the black king. }
