{ A typical motive. Let's take a look at it. Why do we exchange the black doubled pawn?   First, even if d4 is a doubled pawn, it's not that weak, the knight of c6 covers and also ...Qf6 can strengthen it. Moreover, it restricts our natural development with Nc3.   What do we achieve with c3?   We quickly develop our knight to c3 and have opened up the position. Later we can often use the c-file to build up pressure against c7.   If Black doesn't capture on c3, we capture ourselves. ...Nxd4 then comes with tempo, but the knight won't stay long. If Black covers it with ...c5 we always have Be3 and Black is left with many weaknesses. }
12... Kg8 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Qd3 Nc6 15. O-O Kh7 16. Nc3
{ Since we can often achieve such structures, let's take a closer look and try to understand why White has a big advantage here.   Our advantage no longer lies in the development advantage, Black could play ...Rf8 and ...Kg8 to complete the artificial castling.   Instead, our advantage lies in the pawn structure. White has two pawns more on the kingside, while Black has the majority on the queenside. But why exactly are our extra pawns stronger?   ➤ Mobility: It's quite easy to play f2-f4 @@StartBracket@@and perhaps f4-f5-f6@@EndBracket@@ with great control over the centre than ... c7-c5 or ... d6-d5.   ➤ King security: In a middlegame it is often advantageous to have more pawns on the kingside. This often allows the simple plan of exchanging pawns, after which the opponent's king has less pawn protection than yours.   ➤ Stability: It is also possible to play f2-f3 first, bring up pieces and then attack. the construct with pawns on f3 and e4 is extremely stable, as the pawn chain is not weak on the half-open lines e and f. The situation is different for Black: On the half-open c-file, the c7-pawn is potentially weak and needs the sc6-pawn as a shield. If the c-pawn were to move, the d-pawn will become weak on the half-open d-file. }
