{ The starting position of the Italian Opening. White brings the bishop out to c4 from where he is eyeing the square f7.  Black has two fully-fledged replies here:  3...Bc5  and  3...Nf6  , which will make up the main part of these chapters on the Italian Opening. All other replies by Black are discussed in Chapter 6.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  is a different move order, but it allows Black to leave our repertoire with  4...Nf6!?  .   Therefore we choose the move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  in order to meet  3...Nf6  with  4.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  with  4.d4  . }
3... Bc5 4. d4
{ A forcing move, White immediately sets up threats and Black has to make decisions early on. This makes the move very dangerous, especially at beginner and club level. }
4... exd4 5. Ng5
{ A rare and very forcing move that immediately confronts Black with the weakness of the f7-pawn. We should memorise 2 basic rules.  ➤ Our plan is to capture on f7 in any case, even if Black protects with  5...Ne5  or  5...Nh6  . This always works because after  6.Nxf7  Nxf7  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  we win back the bishop on c5 with 8  .Qh5+  .  ➤ On ...Bb4+ @@StartBracket@@to remove the bishop from c5 so that Qh5+ won't be a double attack@@EndBracket@@ we always reply c2-c3 with a counterattack on the bishop. }
5... Nh6
{ The only good reply. Black places the knight on the edge, but brings a new piece into play and prepares castling. Since Black would have no problems after castling, we strike immediately despite the protection. }
6. Nxf7
{ I recommend taking with the knight first, even if it makes no difference in the majority of cases and only leads to a transposition. Nevertheless, in my opinion 6. Nxf7 is more accurate, because here Black has fewer options, namely only ...Nxf7 and ...Bb4+.  In the case of  6.Bxf7+  Nxf7  7.Nxf7  Black would have a greater choice, but we don't want to allow that. In addition to  7...Kxf7  and  7...Bb4  , Black could also try  7...Qh4  or  7...Qe7  . We avoid this with our move order. }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+
{ Now comes the second capture with check and Black has practically no choice. }
