9. Qxc5
{ 9.Qd5+?!  would only help the black king to leave the centre faster. } 9...
d5 10. O-O
{ White removes the king from the centre and is ready for exd5.  The direct  10.exd5  would have resulted in  10...Re8+  . Black doesn't have much choice now. }
10... dxe4 11. c3 Re8 12. cxd4 Qxd4 13. Qg5
{ White avoids the queen exchange and hopes to maintain attacking chances against the weakened black king. }
13... Bf5
{ 13...Qf6  leads to positions similar to the main variation.  14.Qxf6+  Kxf6  15.Nc3  . White also threatens Nd5+ and Nxc7, ...Be6 or ...Rd8 are not possible because otherwise the e4-pawn would be captured. }
14. Nc3
{ For one pawn White has a sustained initiative on the dark squares. The bishop on f5 has also become passive because it has to protect the e4-pawn.   White can continue with e.g. Qh4 and Be3 or Bg5 and Black must organise themselves well to withstand the attack. It's also important that the queens stay on the board, otherwise Black is even better. }
14... Qf6 { The queen exchange doesn't work for Black here. } 15. Qxf6+ Kxf6
16. Nd5+ { And the fork on c7 will follow. White wins material. } *

