{ The only good reply. Black places the knight on the edge, but brings a new piece into play and prepares castling. Since Black would have no problems after castling, we strike immediately despite the protection. }
6. Nxf7
{ I recommend taking with the knight first, even if it makes no difference in the majority of cases and only leads to a transposition. Nevertheless, in my opinion 6. Nxf7 is more accurate, because here Black has fewer options, namely only ...Nxf7 and ...Bb4+.  In the case of  6.Bxf7+  Nxf7  7.Nxf7  Black would have a greater choice, but we don't want to allow that. In addition to  7...Kxf7  and  7...Bb4  , Black could also try  7...Qh4  or  7...Qe7  . We avoid this with our move order. }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+
{ Now comes the second capture with check and Black has practically no choice. }
7... Kxf7 8. Qh5+ g6
{ The best reply. Black must rely on dynamics and quickly seek counterplay. The weakening of the black squares f6-g7-h6 is accepted. }
9. Qxc5
{ 9.Qd5+?!  would only help the black king to leave the centre faster. } 9...
d5 10. O-O
{ White removes the king from the centre and is ready for exd5.  The direct  10.exd5  would have resulted in  10...Re8+  . Black doesn't have much choice now. }
10... dxe4 11. c3 Bf5 12. cxd4 Qxd4 13. Qb5
{ Since Black has a number of possibilities here, I think it makes little sense to analyse them move by move. Instead, let's note a few points to better understand the position and the plans:   ➤ Black has an extra pawn on e4. But that's the only advantage Black has. In addition, the pawn on e4 is weak. Black will try to exchange queens and claim the extra pawn in the endgame.   ➤ White therefore always tries to keep the queens on the board.   ➤ White develops with Nc3 and Be3/f4/g5. Since Black has placed all their pawns on light squares, the dark squares are weakened. This weakening is reinforced by the opposite-coloured bishops. At a suitable opportunity, White can launch an attack on the black squares. }
*

