d6 10. Qc4+ Be6 11. Qe2
{ Here Black has tried out a lot of possibilities, i.e. no clear path has yet been established for Black, or Black was often left on their own.   In my opinion, the white position offers good chances for an advantage in practice. Let's take a look at some of Black's attempts: }
11... Re8 12. O-O
{ Black basically has two approaches here.  ➤ Slow play and improving the pieces in their own ranks - White can also strengthen: Bf4-Bg3/  Bh6  , Nd2 and then sometimes f4-f5 with an attack. This can quickly become very dangerous for Black.  ➤ Direct opening of the centre with  12...d5  - White typically replies with  13.f3  to open the f-file after  13...dxe4  14.fxe4+  and not allow the black bishop the f5-square. }
12... Kg8 13. Bf4 Qd7 14. Nd2
{ White is already better and Black has no clear plan, while White has clear ideas with Rae1, Bh6 and f4-f5. }
14... Rf8 { A mistake which only accelerates White's plans. } 15. Bh6 Rf7 16.
f4 { White has a big initiative on the kingside. } *

