[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Two Knights Defense: 3...Nf6 Sidelines"]
[Black "11A | Two Knights Defense with 4...Bc5 | 5...Kf8 / 7...h6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 Bc5
{ The Traxler Gambit. In my opinion a questionable reply, after which White gets a big advantage. }
5. Bxf7+
{ Forcing and strong.   5.Nxf7  would not be so clear because Black could create complications with the counter-attack  5...Bxf2+  . }
5... Kf8
{ This is less accurate than  5...Ke7  , Black traps the rook in the corner. }
6. Bb3
{ It is always important that we retreat the bishop soon after a capture on f7. Otherwise the bishop itself becomes a target. Here Black threatened 6...h6 winning the bishop or knight:  6.O-O ??  h6  . }
6... Qe8
{ Black tries to quickly create counterplay on the kingside, for example with  7.--  Qg6  or  7...h6  8.Nf3  Qh5  . }
7. d3
{ White protects e4 and the knight on g5.  After  7.Nf7  Black must save the rook with  7...Rg8  . But then White would have nothing better than to retreat the knight. Otherwise the knight itself might become a target, for example if ...Na5 follows later to eliminate the defender of the knight @@StartBracket@@the bishop on b3@@EndBracket@@. After the retreat  8.Ng5  the b3-bishop is attacking the rook. Black can then play  8...Rh8  and we would have the same position on the board as two moves earlier. }
7... h6 8. Nf3
{ 8.Nf7??  would be too greedy, the knight only puts itself in danger. White should instead be content with the extra pawn and try to consolidate their position.  8...Rh7∓ }
8... Qh5 9. Be3
{ A key move. White exchanges the strong bishop. If Black captures on e3, the e3-pawn controls the outposts d4 and f4. In addition, the g2-pawn can be covered from the side with Qe2.   White then aims for long castling, while the black king is not optimally positioned on the now open f-file. }
9... Bb6
{ Black does not want to capture on e3 themselves, but hopes to set up threats with ...d7-d6 and ...Bg4. ...Bg4 is often the only attempt that can cause White problems, so let's see how we can counter the idea. }
10. Nc3 d6 11. Ne2
{ After the following Ng3 the black queen has to move away and the bishop on g4 alone doesn't cause us any problems because we can chase it away with h2-h3. }
11... Bg4 12. Ng3 Bxf3
{ The alternative to the queen's retreat. Black does weaken the white structure, but only with many defences. White has a clearly better endgame with an extra pawn. }
13. Qxf3 Qxf3 14. gxf3
{ White can resolve the doubled pawn with f3-f4 or simply become active on the g-file themselves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Two Knights Defense: 3...Nf6 Sidelines"]
[Black "11A | Two Knights Defense with 4...Bc5 | 5...Ke7 / 8...Bxe3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 Bc5
{ The Traxler Gambit. In my opinion a questionable reply, after which White gets a big advantage. }
5. Bxf7+
{ Forcing and strong.   5.Nxf7  would not be so clear because Black could create complications with the counter-attack  5...Bxf2+  . }
5... Ke7 6. Bb3
{ It is always important that we retreat the bishop soon after capturing on f7. Otherwise the bishop itself becomes a target. Here Black threatened  6.--  h6  with winning the bishop or knight. }
6... Rf8 7. d3 Qe8
{ 7...Bxf2+??  . Don't be afraid of this capture, Black only has a double check afterwards, but then the attack is quickly over.  8.Kxf2  Nxe4+  9.Kg1  Nf2  . Even if Black captures on h1, White has a material advantage. White can simply play Qe2, but Qh5 followed by Nf7 with an attack is even stronger. }
8. Be3
{ A key move. White exchanges the strong bishop. If Black captures on e3 the e3-pawn controls the outposts d4 and f4. In addition, the g2-pawn can be covered from the side with Qe2. White then often aims for long castling. }
8... Bxe3 9. fxe3 Qg6 10. Nf3
{ A tactical finesse, if Black captures on g2, the g7-pawn will also fall. The white king will then castle to the queenside and is not in danger. }
10... d6 11. Qd2
{ White protects g2 and then continues with Nc3 and O-O-O, with a clear advantage. }
*

