[White "11) Two Knights Defense: 3...Nf6 Sidelines"]
[Black "11B | Two Knights Defense with 4...d5 | 5...b5 / 6...Qxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5
{ The main and only good reply. Black must interrupt the diagonal of the white bishop to fend off the attack against f7. }
5. exd5 b5 6. Bf1
{ A paradoxical retreat, what is the idea? If Black continues with  6...Nd4  , the bishop should not be within reach of the knight.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/p1p2ppp/2n2n2/1p1Pp1N1/2B5/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq b6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bxb5  Qxd5!?  7.Nc3  . This doesn't work so well with the bishop on  b5  , because after  7...Qxg2  the g2-pawn would be lost. }
6... Qxd5 7. Nc3
{ Now White can develop the knight with tempo and then capture on b5 with the bishop. In this order Black cannot capture on g2 and is worse off. }
7... Qc5 8. Bxb5 Be7 9. d3
{ White is slightly better, Black has more pawn islands and the queen on c5 is strangely positioned and can be chased later with Nge4 or Be3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Two Knights Defense: 3...Nf6 Sidelines"]
[Black "11B | Two Knights Defense with 4...d5 | 5...b5 / 6...Nd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5
{ The main and only good reply. Black must interrupt the diagonal of the white bishop to fend off the attack against f7. }
5. exd5 b5 6. Bf1
{ A paradoxical retreat, what is the idea? If Black continues with  6...Nd4  , the bishop should not be within reach of the knight.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/p1p2ppp/2n2n2/1p1Pp1N1/2B5/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq b6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bxb5  Qxd5!?  7.Nc3  . This doesn't work so well with the bishop on  b5  , because after  7...Qxg2  the g2-pawn would be lost. }
6... Nd4 7. c3 Nxd5 8. cxd4 Qxg5 9. Bxb5+ Kd8
{ 9...Bd7?  is a mistake. The black position is bad, so complications must be sought at all costs. This is usually achieved with ...Bb7 and dangerous threats on the long diagonal. After exchanging the light-squared bishops, Black no longer has any hope of counterplay and White is better without any worries.  10.Bxd7+  Kxd7  11.O-O  Nf4  12.g3!  . One last important detail. Next comes d2-d3 and White ends the development, while the black king will never find a safe place. White is clearly better.   @@StartBracket@@  12.Qf3?  . This natural-looking move would be a big mistake, because Black can renew the mating threats and keeps the initiative.  12...e4  13.Qxe4  Qg4!!  . Now Nh3 threatens to win a queen.  14.Qf3  . White still seems to have everything under control, but Black has a nice solution.   @@StartBracket@@  14.Qxa8?  Nh3+  15.Kh1  Qe2!  . The threatened mates can only be delayed and prevented with great material losses. @@StartBracket@@15... Nxf2+ would lead to perpetual check, but the text move is even better.@@EndBracket@@  16.Qd5+  Bd6  17.Qf5+  Kd8  18.Rg1  Nxf2+  . Black wins the queen and the game.@@EndBracket@@  14...Qxf3!  . A little surprising. Black enters the endgame despite two pawns down.  15.gxf3  Nd3!  . On closer inspection it becomes clear that White cannot be happy. The entire queenside is not developed - the knight on d3 paralyses the entire white position.@@EndBracket@@ }
10. O-O Bb7 11. Qf3
{ A key move. White voluntarily places the queen on the bishop's diagonal. The black knight cannot yet move away, as the bishop on b7 is unprotected. }
11... Rb8 { Prepares to move the knight, but White can ignore everything. } 12.
dxe5
{ White collects another pawn and is already ready to bring the c1-bishop into play with tempo with d2-d4. Black can now try various moves, but none work well, the least evil is  12...Ne3  - on all other moves White is already winning. }
12... Nc3 13. dxc3
{ White captures on c3 with a counter-attack on the black queen, Black loses by material. }
