[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5
{ The main and only good reply. Black must interrupt the diagonal of the white bishop to fend off the attack against f7. }
5. exd5 b5 6. Bf1
{ A paradoxical retreat, what is the idea? If Black continues with  6...Nd4  , the bishop should not be within reach of the knight.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/p1p2ppp/2n2n2/1p1Pp1N1/2B5/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq b6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bxb5  Qxd5!?  7.Nc3  . This doesn't work so well with the bishop on  b5  , because after  7...Qxg2  the g2-pawn would be lost. }
6... Nxd5 7. Bxb5 Bb7 8. Qh5
{ This has only been played once. We try to confuse Black with our move order.   8.d4  exd4  9.O-O  Be7  10.Qh5  is the normal order and the main variation. With our move order Black can never achieve the same setup, because Be7 is never possible again - otherwise a capture on f7 would follow. }
8... g6
{ This looks natural, but forces Black to defend very precisely afterwards. }
9. Qf3
{ Black's next moves are all forced, otherwise White already has a decisive advantage. }
9... Qd7 10. Nc3 Ndb4 11. O-O h6 12. a3 hxg5 13. axb4
{ The middlegame is balanced, but Black still has to act very precisely, I think White has the better chances here. }
