9... O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. Bb5 c6
{ The critical move, but I think it's unlikely that Black is still 'in the book' here. At first glance it looks as if ...c7-c6 would simply lose a pawn. }
12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Nxc6 Qb6
{ The key idea. Black gets counterplay by attacking the bishop and knight, and the advance with ...e4-e3 and the opening of the white king is also in the air. }
14. Qa4 e3 15. Bxe3 Bxe3 16. Nxa5 Bxf2+ 17. Kh1 Re1 18. Nd2
{ A long forced variation. Black is a little better, but White can hold things together. In practice, however, I think this line is very unlikely. Black is currently still two pawns down...Who would guess that Black has the advantage here - in particular, Black must have seen it all at 11...c6...no easy feat. }
