9... O-O 10. O-O Nxc4
{ A continuation that gives White hope, Black won't get the pawn back so easily afterwards and must use the dynamic advantages. If White consolidates, the white position is often preferable due to the extra pawn. }
11. dxc4 Bd6 12. h3
{ Prophylaxis. The g4-square is a good stepping stone for the black bishop or knight to launch an attack. We therefore take these options out of the position as a precaution. }
12... Re8 13. Be3 Qe7
{ Another attacking idea, but not so dangerous if we discover it early. Black wants ...Qe5 with a mating threat on h2. }
14. Nb5
{ Easiest. Without the d6-bishop there will be no mate. Black must keep the bishop, every exchange helps White because the extra pawn will count in the endgame. }
14... Be5 15. Nd2 c6 16. d6 Bxd6 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. c5
{ The position is balanced, but everyone has their chances. White can try to use the outposts on the d-file with the minor pieces, for example with Re1 and Qe2, followed by Nc4-d6. }
