1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d4 Nxd4
{ A rare but good move. In my opinion, it is rarely seen in practice for two reasons:  1@@EndBracket@@ Black must react to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  with  3...exd4  . Our move order is rarer and it's not worth it for Black studying another reply.  2@@EndBracket@@ After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/8/2b1p3/2BnP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxe5  , Black has to play  5...Qe7  and allow themselves to be captured on f7, then play further accurate moves, which many players find impractical in a minor variation. }
5. Nxe5 Qf6
{ Even a world-class player like Sam Sevian is surprised and is already losing after 5 moves.   5...Qe7!  would be correct, because after...  6.Bxf7+  Kf8  , the c5-bishop is protected and Nd3 doesn't work. }
6. Nd3
{ Not the best, but also good, White has a clear advantage. Black is badly coordinated and the queen on f6 is a good target for White.   6.Bxf7+!  The capture is best, White then saves the piece with Nd3. Black is left a pawn down and with a weak king.  6...Kf8  7.Nd3+- }
6... Bb6 7. Nc3 c6 8. e5 Qe7 9. O-O Kf8
{ Not a move you like to play, but good advice was already expensive...   ➤  9...Nh6?  10.Bxh6  gxh6  11.Ne4  and White ends up with the knight on d6 or f6 and Black has a losing position.   ➤  9...d6?  . Opening the e-file is very dangerous for Black, for example:  10.exd6!  Qxd6  11.Ne4  Qe7  12.Re1  Now there is a threat of a queen win.  12...Be6  13.c3  Nf5  14.Bxe6  fxe6  15.Ne5  Black cannot complete the development, the natural ...Nf6 fails. If Black does not play ...Nf6, Qh5+ follows with a win.  15...Nf6  16.Nxf6+ }
10. Re1 Nh6 11. Ne4 Qh4 12. Bg5 Qg4 13. c3 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Ne6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16.
Bxh6 gxh6 17. Nd6
{ White is winning, the entire black queenside remains paralyzed. } 17... Bc7
18. Nf4 Bxd6 19. Rxd6 Rg8 20. Nh5 Rg5 21. Nf6 Ke7 22. f4 Rf5 23. Rd4
{ After  23.g3!  everything remains stable and Black never gets rid of the d6-rook. Nakamura probably thought that Black was threatening ...Rxf6 followed by ...Kxd6. But White has one more trick and wins!  23...Rxf6  24.exf6+  Kxd6  25.Rd1+!  Kc7  26.f7  and now White gets a new queen. }
23... c5 24. Rde4 d5 25. R4e3 Rxf4 26. Rh3 Bd7 27. Rg3 Be8 28. Rg7+ Bf7 29.
