[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ 3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  Nf6  5.O-O  d5  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Ng5  was the actual move order played in the game, but I've inserted our repertoire move order. We reach the same position through a transposition. }
3... Nf6 4. Ng5 d5
{ The main and only good reply. Black must interrupt the diagonal of the white bishop to fend off the attack against f7. }
5. exd5 Nxd5
{ This is popular at beginner level, but it's a big mistake. White can now play  6.Nxf7  , but I recommend the more solid  6.d4  . This game shows that White can also gain an advantage with it and win quickly. }
6. d4 { 6.Nxf7±  is also good, but outside our repertoire. } 6... exd4
{ 6...Nxd4  This is the lesser evil, but here too Black has to solve problems and is worse even with the best play.  7.c3± }
7. O-O
{ Rapid development is the key to success, the opponent's king is in the center and the e-file is already open. }
7... Be6 8. Re1 Qd7 9. Nxf7
{ My favourite move in this variation. The capture on f7 is even stronger than the capture on e6. Also surprising, because f7 seemed well protected - but appearances are deceptive. }
9... Kxf7
{ 9...Qxf7  10.Bxd5  , Black cannot recapture because of the pin on the e-file. }
10. Qf3+ Kg8
{ ➤  10...Kg6??  11.Rxe6++-  with mate soon after Bd3+.   ➤  10...Ke8  11.Bxd5+-  . Here too White wins back the piece and the pin on the e-file is decisive. }
11. Rxe6 Ncb4 12. Re5 { threatens Rxd5 with mating attack. } 12... c6 13. Na3
{ 13.a3  would be my choice, the knight cannot move away, otherwise Rxd5 follows followed by Bxd5 with a winning position. }
13... Na6
{ Black was already losing, but this voluntary retreat hastens the downfall. }
14. Rxd5 Qf7 15. Rxd4
{ 15.Rd8  leads to mate the quickest, but the continuation of the game is also good enough. }
